bottom_line: A rich-toned, floral-driven espresso, particularly expressive in cappuccino-scaled milk.
title: Guatemala Washed Finca El General Pache M-Plus Espresso

bottom_line: A friendly, accessible Guatemala cup: crispy sweet with nut and chocolate throughlines.
title: Guatemala Washed Finca El General Pache

bottom_line: An accessible espresso, medium-roasted and balanced, with pleasing chocolate, fruit and floral notes in both straight shot and milk.
title: Guatemala Washed Finca El General Lot Summer End Espresso

bottom_line: A clean natural-processed Colombia cup from an unusual variety of Arabica — fruit-driven and chocolaty.
title: Colombia La Esperanza Natural XO

Coffee Origin: Gayo (also Aceh) growing region, Aceh Province, northern Sumatra, Indonesia
bottom_line: Roast-prominent yet thoroughly integrated, this espresso offers a compelling sweet-savory depth for those who enjoy the style.
title: Indonesia Sumatra Gayo Espresso

bottom_line: A classic washed Ethiopia cup: high-toned, rich and juicy, with notes of stone fruit and flowers throughout.
title: Ethiopia Limu Nano Challa Lot #10

bottom_line: Elegant, lyrical and enchanting, with an integrated presentation of floral, fruit, spice, nut and cocoa tones and an exceptionally balanced and vibrant structure and acidity.
title: Best of Panama GNEP-01 Elida Geisha Green Tip Natural

bottom_line: A cleanly and thoroughly berry-toned natural-processed Geisha with big chocolate notes throughout and satisfying savory underpinnings.
title: Geisha XO

bottom_line: An unabashedly fruit-centered natural-processed Geisha with big florals to match the fruit and compelling, subtle spice undertones.
title: Colombia Finca La Maria Geisha Natural

bottom_line: An exquisitely balanced natural-processed Geisha with the deep, sweet complexity the type can offer without a hint of ferment: crisply sweet fruit top and bottom notes, along with rich florals and chocolate tones in the mid-palate, all enhanced by a whisper of sandalwood.
title: Panama Finca Kalithea Natural Geisha

bottom_line: Extravagant florals and spice-toned cocoa notes characterize this deeply sweet, washed-processed Panama cup with a nuanced yet omnipresent umami impulse.
title: Panama Hacienda La Esmeralda Super Mario 6 Geisha

bottom_line: An impressively smooth, coherent structure supports a quietly pleasing set of Geisha aromatics. Should satisfy those who may find the full-on Panama Geisha fireworks a bit much but who still enjoy the distinctive character of this rare variety.
title: Panama Geisha Alto Jaramillo

bottom_line: A deep berry-toned cup with a juicy hint of sweet ferment and rich cocoa notes throughout.
title: Colombia Laderas del Tapias Estate Natural Geisha

bottom_line: A beautifully structured natural-processed Ethiopia Gesha, with striking sweetness pleasingly complicated by notes of aromatic resin and tropical fruit.
title: Gesha Village Natural Lot #19

bottom_line: A pleasingly coherent coffee that is both sweet and savory in harmonious balance, with floral and fruit tones throughout and an herbaceous note that grounds and enriches the whole.
title: Gesha Village 1931 Lot 27

bottom_line: A high-toned natural-processed Ethiopia that is fruit-forward without a hint of ferment.
title: Ethiopia Guji Girma Natural

bottom_line: A chocolate- and fruit-toned natural-processed Ethiopia coffee with a hint of appealing sweet ferment throughout.
title: Ethiopia Limu Lema Edeto

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, south-central Ethiopia
bottom_line: A delicately complex and nuanced coffee, subtly composed around fruit and musky floral tones.
title: Ethiopia Sidamo Gora Kone

bottom_line: An interpretation of classic espresso, with rich, smoky-toned chocolate alongside sweet fruit. Particularly pleasing in three parts milk.
title: Classic Nine Espresso

bottom_line: For those who prefer a darker-roasted espresso, this unapologetically smoke-forward and chocolaty cup offers an accessible profile.
title: Espresso Blend No. 10

bottom_line: A lovely espresso whose tartness is integrated with a deep and embracing sweetness.
title: Kebele Village Espresso

bottom_line: A coffee for those who like their washed Ethiopias high-toned and tart-leaning, with an abiding cocoa- and floral-toned sweetness throughout.
title: Kebele Village Ethiopia

bottom_line: An undeniably powerful espresso, and an interesting and engaging interpretation of the ancient Mocha-Java blend concept, combining fruit and flowers from an Ethiopia/Yemen coffee with rich spice and sweet depth from an Indonesia.
title: D31 The New Life

bottom_line: A resonant expression of the traditional Panama washed cup, driven by deep chocolate notes supported by subtle but persistent sweet floral tones. A bargain at $12 for 12 ounces.
title: Panama Finca San Sebastian

bottom_line: A sweet, pleasingly floral coffee animated by berry and cocoa notes throughout.
title: Rwanda Nyarusiza Station

bottom_line: A big-bodied Kenya, zesty, deep, yet delicately layered in the aromatics.
title: Murang’a Kenya

bottom_line: A bold sweet-savory espresso with a striking and original range of aromatics.
title: Murang’a Kenya Espresso

bottom_line: An extremely rare, limited-production coffee procured by Miguel Meza of Paradise Roasters, unique in both backstory and cup.
title: Coffea Diversa Cioiccie

Coffee Origin: Gedeb District, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: A complex, umami- and citrus-driven natural-processed Ethiopia cup that hits all the pleasure spots: sweet, tart and savory in harmonious balance.
title: Yirgacheffe Gedeb G1 Natural

bottom_line: A blend of washed and wet-hulled coffees that reads like a friendly Sumatra: sweetly wood-framed with notes of chocolate and baking spices.
title: Trilogy

bottom_line: A harmonious, lyrical, balanced Kenya coffee, classic in its expression of both sweet and savory impulses.
title: Kenya Kiambu Uklili AA

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: An elegant natural-processed Ethiopia that is fruit-forward without a hint of ferment: crisp, clean, juicy-sweet.
title: Ethiopia Guji Shakisso Natural Lot 24

bottom_line: An integrated, citrus-inflected washed Ethiopia cup with a cocoa throughline and spicy floral notes, particularly in the aroma.
title: Ethiopia Washed Yirgacheffe Nafasha Lot

Coffee Origin: Tecapa Chinameca growing region, Santiago de María, southeastern El Salvador
bottom_line: The nut notes are pleasant but just a front; drink it for its grown-up dry chocolate, zesty lime and elderflower notes that emerge with just a little patience.
title: La Avila SL28 El Salvador

Coffee Origin: Tecapa Chinameca growing region, southeastern El Salvador
bottom_line: Balanced and comprehensive in structure, with a subtle but grand array of aromatics: honey-like flowers, crisp lavender-like flowers, juicy yet savory fruit (we called it roasted pineapple), nut, dry chocolate.
title: El Salvador

Coffee Origin: La Palma, Chalatenango Department, northwestern El Salvador
bottom_line: Both delicate and resonant, animated by sweet, honeyish nut and lime-toned citrus.
title: Talquezalar El Salvador

Coffee Origin: Santa Ana Department, northwestern El Salvador
bottom_line: A nut-toned bitter-savory inclination is lifted majestically by a deep, cherry-like sweetness. Drink it for the contrast, and the big, syrupy mouthfeel.
title: Finca Kilimanjaro Natural

bottom_line: A quietly original Geisha: sweet-savory, complexly aromatic.
title: Finca San Antonio El Salvador

bottom_line: Cedary dark chocolate and subtle walnut and peach notes make this a particularly accessible version of the great Pacamara profile.
title: Mario Aguilar Grand Cru El Salvador

bottom_line: Almost two coffees, one dominated by a bracing bitter-leaning structure, the other sweet and complexly aromatic. Enjoy it for its paradox and its particularly syrupy mouthfeel.
title: José Flores El Salvador Natural

bottom_line: Delicately juicy, lemon-and chocolate-saturated, an exceptional example of a great Central Africa coffee in a Nespresso-compatible capsule.
title: Cup of Excellence Rwanda Champion

bottom_line: A sweetly fermenty natural-processed Ethiopia turned slightly more austere by bittersweet floral and spicy aromatic wood notes.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Worka Gotiti Natural

bottom_line: A fruit bomb of a coffee with an abundance of smoky wood and savory tones suggesting pickled vegetables — odd perhaps, but a nice ballast for the big fruit.
title: Cold-Drip Blend “Dionysus”

Coffee Origin: Odo Shakiso District, Guji Zone, Oromia region, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: Lovely Ethiopia natural: cleanly fruit-toned, crisp, resonant, and sweet through and through.
title: Ethiopia Kayon Mountain Natural

Coffee Origin: ochere, Yirgacheffe growing region, south-central Ethiopia
bottom_line: A juicy, rich natural-processed Yirgacheffe cup with clean fruit and cocoa tones throughout and an appealing savory edge.
title: Ethiopia Natural Yirgacheffe Blue Donkey Lot

bottom_line: A single-origin espresso from Guatemala pleasingly floral-prominent in both the straight shot and with milk. Rich, crisp, high-toned.
title: Guatemala Guayabales Single-Origin Espresso

bottom_line: A pleasing umami-driven Kenya that foreground notes of sweet, ripe tomato with enveloped in rich florals and crisp chocolate.
title: Kenya Chania Estate

bottom_line: A richly bittersweet Guatemala cup punctuated by pretty notes of citrus zest throughout.
title: Guatemala Los Santos

bottom_line: Exhilarating, bright, balmy: like drinking a spring day with a cocoa chaser.
title: Geisha Village Auction Lot #11

bottom_line: A complex, nuanced expression of a natural-processed Yirgacheffe coffee: fruit-forward, balanced, juicy and multi-layered — the fruit-centered genius of a natural conveyed with the completeness and inevitability of a classic.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Chelelektu Natural

bottom_line: A classic Kenya cup: sweet, tart, juicy all wrapped together with deep-toned red fruit and spicy floral notes.
title: Kenya Kimaruri

bottom_line: A pretty, fruit-prominent natural-processed coffee expressing balance and finesse.
title: Zambia Kateshi Natural

bottom_line: Rather than the typical Kenya black currant and cocoa profile, this equally remarkable Kenya is driven by the intensity of the musky/rich elements and the juicy stone fruit and citrus.
title: Kenya Handege

bottom_line: Quiet, round, crisply balanced, with sweet stone fruit and cocoa supported by savory-leaning nut and oak.
title: Kauai Estate Reserve Sun-Dried Typica

Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca Department, western Colombia
bottom_line: Grandly intense yet sweetly agreeable: seethes with complex floral and brightly juicy fruit notes.

bottom_line: A sweetly bright yet roundly savory rendition of the rare Sidra varietal.
title: Ecuador Loja Clara Sidra Natural Taza Dorada #2

bottom_line: A compelling natural espresso — fully loaded with chocolaty, fruit-forward adventure.
title: The Natural

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, south-central Ethiopia
bottom_line: A thoroughly enjoyable fruit-forward espresso with considerable complexity, expressed by the roaster through the romantic notion written on the retail bag, “The road to love is very happy, Blowing the horn at 3pm.”
title: Ethiopia Sidamo G4 Natural Espresso

bottom_line: An impressive example of Mexico-grown Geisha: elegant, delicate, nuanced, and deeply engaging.
title: Green-Tip Geisha

Coffee Origin: Sandy Bay Valley, Saint Helena Island
bottom_line: An extremely rare, limited-production coffee procured by Miguel Meza of Paradise Roasters, well worth sampling for its balanced, pleasingly complex cup profile.
title: Saint Helena Island Peaberry

bottom_line: A rare opportunity to sample a fine specialty coffee emerging valiantly from a neglected coffee-growing region where 90 percent of coffee grown is of the Robusta species and almost all is consumed locally.
title: Philippines Sitio Naguey Natural

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, south-central Ethiopia
bottom_line: Deep, floral and cleanly fruit-toned, with prominent notes of dried stone fruit, spicy florals, and rich aromatic wood.
title: Ethiopia Guji Queen Honey

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, south-central Ethiopia
bottom_line: A sweet-toned natural Ethiopia cup that supplements ripe berry notes and dark chocolate with inviting hints of rich sandalwood.
title: Ethiopia Civet Sidama Papilio Natural

Coffee Origin: Kochere Woreda, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: Fragrant jasmine and pungent incense-like notes in distinguish this crisply graceful wet-processed Ethiopia.
title: Banco Gotete Ethiopia

bottom_line: A fine darker-roasted espresso; the aromatic roast notes are saturated with Ethiopia chocolate and flowers. Especially attractive in the milk shot.
title: Ethiopia Washed Guji Dimtu Espresso

bottom_line: A mesmerizing Kenya that is equally balanced among sweet, tart and savory impulses, with a particularly lively acidity.
title: Barichu Double

bottom_line: A creative blend of washed and natural-processed coffees that complement each other with primary notes of both chocolate and fruit, both in the straight shot and in milk.
title: GA 400 Espresso

bottom_line: A friendly, engaging PNG cup with leading notes of deep florals supported by sweet nut tones throughout the profile.
title: Papua New Guinea Timuza

bottom_line: An espresso whose expression in the straight shot is classic Kenya in a dance of vibrant sweet and savory and shimmering aromatic complexity; in milk, it’s an almost addictive fine dessert with an umami edge.
title: Rukera Espresso

bottom_line: A floral- and spice-toned cup: balanced, complex, multilayered.
title: Colombia Pink Bourbon El Corazon

bottom_line: A Kenya espresso blend, through and through, with the hallmark brightness and savory edge associated with this origin’s classically sweet-tart structure.
title: L2 Love Espresso Blend

bottom_line: A “classic” third-wave espresso that presents bittersweet citrus, rich floral and lemony herb notes, all rounded by chocolate throughout.
title: Guatemala-Ethiopia Espresso Blend

bottom_line: Suggests traditional Italian-style espresso, bittersweet and accessible, with especially pretty chocolate notes.
title: Black Meow Blend

bottom_line: An unusual espresso blend, sweet and tart, with intriguing spice notes suggesting cardamom.
title: Karibu Espresso Blend

bottom_line: An avant-garde espresso blend of nine different natural-processed coffees — ideal for the lover of unabashedly fruit-toned coffees.
title: Sun Sun Sun Sun Sun Sun Sun Sun Sun Blend

Coffee Origin: Hambela district, Oromia growing region, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: A pleasing Ethiopia natural: balanced, accessible, sweetly fruit-forward.
title: Ethiopia Hambela 1 Organic Natural Alaka

Coffee Origin: Ibicoara Municipality, Chapada Diamantina region, Bahia State, Brazil
bottom_line: A solid Brazil natural: clean, deeply sweet, with a pleasing savory throughline.

bottom_line: A friendly, easy-drinking Costa Rica cup, lively with citrusy herb notes and sweet florals.
title: Costa Rica Coto Brus-La Amistad

bottom_line: A big, richly, authoritative sweet-savory Kenya, lifted and animated by shimmers of flowers and tart citrus.

bottom_line: An inviting coffee from Peru, characterized by deep florals and balanced by notes of stone fruit and citrus zest.
title: Peru Antonio Regalado Diaz El Huyacan La Palma

bottom_line: Sweet and savory in equal measure, with a tart throughline: complex, nuanced, and multilayered.
title: Bella Carmona Guatemala

bottom_line: A heady coffee with clean, confident fruit notes throughout, supported by deep chocolate and spice-toned florals.
title: Peru Natural Jose Herrera Lot 21

bottom_line: An attractively bright and fruit-centered coffee with unique and inviting savory elements.
title: Burundi Dukorerikawa Natural

title: Guatemala Acatenango Washed Lot 503 Espresso

bottom_line: Pleasingly chocolate-toned, especially in milk, and quite balanced throughout, as the blend name suggests.

title: Old Crow Cuppa Joe

bottom_line: A highly portable, savory-leaning instant coffee with lingering notes of salty and sweet.
title: Single-Origin Colombian Medium Roast

Coffee Origin: Sidamo (also Sidama) growing region, south-central Ethiopia
bottom_line: A balanced, friendly natural-processed Ethiopia cup characterized by cocoa-toned stone fruit and delicate florals.
title: Ethiopia Sidamo Sasaba

bottom_line: A good choice for lovers of natural-processed coffees who prefer to avoid even a hint of sweet ferment; this cup is all clean fruit and florals.

Coffee Origin: Gedeb District, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: A vibrant, high-toned washed-processed Ethiopia cup with rich floral and citrus tones throughout, all enveloped in dark chocolate.
title: Ethiopia Gedeb Worka Sakaro

bottom_line: An intriguing Colombia cup with deep savory-sweetness, top notes of elegant flowers and undertones of earthy-sweet pipe tobacco.

bottom_line: A beautiful fruit- and floral-toned Colombia cup with undertones of rich chocolate and resonant sandalwood.
title: Colombia Pink Bourbon

bottom_line: A lush, high-toned natural Colombia cup, as clean and bright as its name implies.
title: Crystalina

bottom_line: A lighter-roasted blend of fine Ethiopia coffees for those who enjoy sweetly tart, high-toned espressos.
title: Fruit Adventure Espresso Blend

bottom_line: A moderately dark-roasted espresso blend that stays impressively true to the nut theme announced by its name.
title: Nuts Espresso Blend

bottom_line: A classic Kenya cup: bright, balanced, sweetly savory and deeply vibrant throughout.
title: Kenya Kiambu Gititu AA

Coffee Origin: Kona growing district, Big Island of Hawai'i
bottom_line: A pretty, richly fruit-toned natural-processed Kona cup, organic-certified.

bottom_line: A friendly, cocoa- and nut-toned Guatemala espresso, both as straight shot and in cappuccino-scaled milk.
title: Guatemala Finca El General BlackLand Lot

bottom_line: A coffee that in its wild, unruly intensity and intriguing aromatic drama challenges the boundaries of what coffee is and can be.
title: Ninety Plus Gesha Estates JBC Custom Lot #252

bottom_line: A balanced, poised espresso in the newer, brighter style.
title: ASOPCAFA Espresso

bottom_line: Crisp, briskly dry yet sweet; delicately chocolate- and nut-toned.

bottom_line: A quietly original coffee: big-bodied, low-toned, crisply sweet-savory.
title: Natural Burundi Nemba

bottom_line: A classic SL-28 cup, juicy-sweet with leading notes of red fruit and spice-toned sweet florals, supported by suggestions of buttery toffee.

bottom_line: An engaging natural-processed Ka’u coffee, fruit-driven, with a foundation of pipe tobacco and cocoa notes.

bottom_line: Richly floral and cleanly fruit-toned, an impressive and increasingly familiar style of natural- and honey-processed coffee from Ka’u producers.

bottom_line: An opportunity to taste one of the world’s rarest coffees, a hybrid that exemplifies the persistence and ingenuity of coffee scientists.
title: Estate-Grown Mamo

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: Complete, balanced, yet striking and original espresso.
title: Australian Blend Espresso

bottom_line: A deftly dark-roasted Colombia coffee with spicy florals, tropical fruit notes, and a deep molasses-like sweetness.
title: Colombian Supremo

bottom_line: A boldly dark-roasted Colombia coffee that accentuates chocolate and deep floral notes with a pretty throughline of cashew-like nut.
title: Colombian Supremo

bottom_line: An intensely aromatic, roasty wood-framed cup with deep chocolate and savory floral notes.
title: Rwandan

bottom_line: An attractively tart and savory honey-processed coffee. Try it with salty morning dishes, which should develop its subtle, complementary sweetness.

bottom_line: An extraordinary coffee, difficult to characterize in typical coffee language, yet deeply satisfying, ringing with quiet, resonant authority.

bottom_line: A deep, satisfying coffee, accessible yet resonantly complex.

bottom_line: A complex and engaging rendition of the characteristically richly spicy, tobacco-toned, floral-fruity Yemen profile.

bottom_line: The first coffee from Malaysian Borneo to be roasted for retail consumers in the U.S. and a promising new project in a region not yet known for specialty coffee.

Coffee Origin: Salgar Municipality, Antioquia Department, west-central Colombia

title: Colombia

bottom_line: Deep, resonant and pleasing. Dry, yet quite plump and juicy.

bottom_line: A roast-toned, richly bittersweet espresso with prominent chocolate character and sweet floral nuance.
title: No. 6 Espresso Blend

bottom_line: A clean, bright natural Sidamo cup: high-toned fruit, deep musk notes, bittersweet complexity.

bottom_line: A superbly structured natural-processed Ethiopia Gesha that leads with clean fruit tones supported by rich cocoa and deep florals.

bottom_line: A pleasing blend whose medium-dark roast profile brings out the coffee’s inherent cocoa tones.
title: Easter Sunrise Blend

bottom_line: A classic Ethiopia cup: juicy-bright with leading notes of stone fruit and cocoa nib.

bottom_line: A shape-shifter of a coffee: brilliant, original, absorbing.

bottom_line: An aromatically bright and rousing Typica cup, high-toned with bittersweet citrus and rich spice notes.

Coffee Origin: Gayo (also Aceh) growing region, Aceh Province, northern Sumatra, Indonesia
bottom_line: Snacking after some work in the garden. The scent of fresh-turned earth and dark chocolate.

Coffee Origin: Gayo (also Aceh) growing region, Aceh Province, northern Sumatra, Indonesia
bottom_line: For lovers of depth and sweet-savory resonance — those who enjoy the roundly sweet/tart/savory character of a fine ripe tomato, for example.

bottom_line: A balanced, accessible single-origin espresso, cocoa- and floral-toned in milk.
title: Ethiopia Sidamo Nansebo Station Espresso

bottom_line: Deeply rich, fruit-toned. Strawberry jam, roasted cacao nib, juniper wood, almond, tiger lily in aroma and cup. Sweetly tart structure; delicate, silky mouthfeel. The richly drying finish centers around crisp fruit notes (strawberry) framed by juniper-like aromatic wood notes.
title: Typica Baishengcun Farm

bottom_line: Hits all the classic Kenya notes: pungent with deep fruit and florals, supported by a simultaneously bright yet savory structure.
title: Kenya Gatomboya AA

bottom_line: A tour-de-force espresso composed of a fruit-driven, spice-toned blend of Colombia, Ethiopia and Kenya coffees: richly bittersweet, with deeply expressed fruit and florals.
title: Flight Seasonal Espresso

bottom_line: A gorgeous fruit- and floral-toned espresso, the pleasures of which are both intensified and deepened in milk, where a tropical theme (coconut, lychee) emerges.
title: A.G.E. Duetto Espresso

bottom_line: A crisply sweet wet-processed Ethiopia cup, delicate yet intriguing in its spice and flowers.
title: Ethiopia Kochere G1 Lot 096/183

bottom_line: A richly sweet, spice-toned washed Ethiopia cup, with a throughline of intriguing bergamot and fennel-like notes.
title: Ethiopia Deri Kochere

bottom_line: An understated Yirgacheffe cup, quiet in aroma, with a balanced sweet-savory through-line carried by apricot and spicy aromatic wood notes.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Chelelektu

bottom_line: A thrilling ride of a Kenya: balanced, deep, rich, and intriguingly spice-toned.
title: Kenya Nyeri Hill Farm

Coffee Origin: Sabanilla de Alajuela growing region, Costa Rica
bottom_line: An engaging natural-processed Costa Rica driven by spicy floral notes and suggestions of dried stone fruit. Organically grown.
title: Costa Rica Cumbres del Poas “Perla Negra”

bottom_line: Original in aromatics and deep in structure. Savory-leaning with rich sweetness and a spice throughline.
title: Gold Mountain Coffee Growers Daniel’s Caturra Microlot

bottom_line: An impressive dried-in-the-fruit or “natural”-processed coffee, a tour-de-force of rich fruit, spicy floral, and sweet herb notes.
title: Santa Maria Natural Yellow Catuai

bottom_line: More elegant than the term “funky” implies; nonetheless will most appeal to those who enjoy coffees that are decidedly driven by the richness of deep fruit notes.
title: Nicaragua Limoncillo Funky

bottom_line: A rich, engaging honey-processed Pacamara cup with a throughline of sweet herb notes.
title: Nicaragua Pacamara Honey Finca Cerro de Jesus

bottom_line: As the coffee’s name implies, the cup is characterized by notes suggesting tangy hard candy (watermelon, green apple), complicated by sweet-toned spices and aromatic wood.
title: Tolliver’s Reserve Nicaragua Gold Mountain Fruit Candy Nanolot

bottom_line: A crisp, balanced sweet-toned cup with the intrigue of pleasingly bitter floral and herb notes.
title: Los Congos Washed

bottom_line: A solid, complexly structured coffee from a roaster that has supported the coffee producers of Nicaragua for decades, through thick and thin. The Smithsonian Bird-Friendly certification is a rare and impeccable environmental credential.
title: Organic Shade-Grown Nicaragua

bottom_line: A confident floral and sweetly spice-toned Nicaragua from trees of the heirloom Bourbon variety: elegant, deeply rich, sweetly and roundly resonant.
title: Nicaragua Un Regalo de Dios Bourbon

bottom_line: An engaging ride of a Nicaragua Gesha: high-toned, balanced, discreetly confident, complete.
title: Jinotega Geisha

bottom_line: A richly floral-toned, chocolaty espresso blend, especially attractive in milk.
title: Bernachon B888 Espresso

bottom_line: Travels seamlessly through sweet fruit, spicy floral and rich aromatic wood notes; surprising but always graceful.
title: Mei-Chu Blend

Coffee Origin: Gedeb District, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: An elegant, sensuous experience of a dried-in-the-fruit or natural-processed Ethiopia coffee. Harmoniously sweet, tart and savory with a stunning range of aromatic intrigue.
title: Gedeb Lot 83 Ethiopia Natural

Coffee Origin: Gedeb District, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: An unusual washed Ethiopia cup, suggesting a very adult version of a chocolate and root beer float perhaps, but with deep floral and fruit complications.
title: Halo Beriti Ethiopia

bottom_line: A flavor-saturated Kenya cup characterized by sweet fruit and floral tones at the top, fine musk and chocolate underneath.
title: Mutitu Kenya

bottom_line: An inviting Guatemala, notable for its savory, tart-leaning sweetness, high-toned and layered.
title: Guaya’b Guatemala

bottom_line: Offers the depth and balance of a fine Pacamara, simultaneously sweet, savory and tart, with a quietly resonant set of aroma and flavor notes.
title: El Aquila Pacamara El Salvador

bottom_line: A washed Ethiopia cup with a lot going on: high-toned fruit, crisply sweet citrus zest, and a confident ballast of herb-laced butterscotch.
title: Ethiopia Konga Sede

bottom_line: A surprising Colombia cup, unconventional in regard to processing method (dried-in-the-fruit full natural), which contributes to a fruit-forward, yet cohesively balanced, profile.
title: Colombia La Guamera

bottom_line: A thrill of a natural-processed Ethiopia: fruit, florals and savory notes in intricate, lively harmony.
title: Static Amaro Gayo Natural Ethiopia

bottom_line: A deeply sweet, richly pungent espresso blend, compelling in its confident spice tones (caraway, licorice root) and balanced sweet-savory-tart structure.
title: Static Cali Classic Espresso

bottom_line: An impressively balanced, energetic chocolate- and stonefruit-toned espresso from Mexico, an origin seldom show-cased in single-origin espressos.
title: Static Dark Star Mexico Espresso

bottom_line: A simultaneously savory-leaning yet floral- and sweet-toned honey-processed coffee.
title: Static Hacienda Sonora Costa Rica

bottom_line: A honey-processed Costa Rica cup, enticing for its high-toned, vivacious herb notes enveloped in suggestions of rich florals and sweet nuts.
title: Static Don Eli La Pastora Tarrazu Costa Rica

bottom_line: A big-bodied Colombia that leads unapologetically and impressively with sweet-toned spice notes.
title: Static Rio Negro Huila Supremo

bottom_line: An inviting honey-processed Ethiopia, with cocoa, fruit and floral notes both rounded and turned gently crisp by a tactful medium-dark roast.
title: Static Ethiopia Koke

bottom_line: An interesting choice for those who prefer to find the sweetness in their cup expressed in floral and aromatic wood notes rather than in the more typical fruit.
title: Static Adado Shara

bottom_line: A roast at the edge between medium and medium-dark promotes pleasant smoke notes in this Guatemala, while still allowing spice, fruit and floral notes to exert their presence and authority.
title: Static San Augustin Guatemala

Coffee Origin: Cerrado growing region, Minas Gerais State, Brazil
bottom_line: An aromatic-wood-framed Brazil peaberry with pretty floral undertones.
title: Static Peaberry Cerrado Brazil

bottom_line: The bittersweet structure, dried fruit notes and vanilla-toned flowers pleasantly nudge this coffee toward a darker roast profile, even though this is a medium-roasted bean.
title: Static Ravens Dark Roast Mexico

bottom_line: A bright, even lyrical, floral- and fruit-driven cup.
title: Shine Day El Salvador

bottom_line: A decisively Kenya cup with classic notes of red currant throughout, grounded and balanced by tropical nut tones and crisply sweet, concentrated florals.
title: Kenya Kirinyaga Baragwi Guama AB

bottom_line: A high-toned, richly sweet-tart espresso, equally attractive as a straight shot or in milk.
title: Guatemala Finca El General Espresso

bottom_line: An appealingly meandering, spice-toned floral cup, centered on the ripe, faintly fermenty blueberry notes often pleasingly characteristic of dried-in-the-fruit or “natural”-processed coffees like this one.
title: Ethiopia Natural Yirgacheffe Adado

bottom_line: A light-footed and crisply elegant Kenya; if the big, emphatic Kenyas are Cabernets, this one is a Pinot Noir.
title: Kenya AA Nyeri

bottom_line: Although Uganda has struggled over the years to produce top Arabica coffees worthy of its excellent terroirs and hard-working growers, producers have clearly succeeded here with this very impressive, quite distinctive offering in the deep, resonant style of the best Central Africa coffees.
title: Uganda Fair Trade Bukonzo

Coffee Origin: LImmu Woreda, Oromia Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: A crisp, high-toned dried-in-the-fruit or “natural”-processed Ethiopia driven by berry notes with a hint of sweet fruit ferment and grounded by intimations of cocoa and sweet herbs.
title: Ethiopia Limmu Organic Kebena Kossa

Coffee Origin: Marcala growing region, La Paz Department, Honduras
bottom_line: Unusual Central America profile, tart but starchy, candyish yet savory. Those who value the sweet/savory coffees of Central Africa origins like Rwanda or Burundi may particularly enjoy this attractive but atypical Honduras.
title: Honduras Finca Jerusalen

bottom_line: A light-footed, vivacious wet-processed Ethiopia cup. Might make a refreshing cold or iced coffee.
title: Ethiopia Shakisso

bottom_line: A nuanced, complex Colombia cup that leads with lush floral notes and stone fruit grounded by suggestions of rich cocoa.
title: Colombia Finca Campoalegre

Coffee Origin: Baringo and Nakura Counties, central Kenya
bottom_line: An elegant and complete Kenya; pungent, delicate yet deep. Think fine red table wines.
title: Kenya Boma AA

bottom_line: Offers a nuanced experience of a dried-in-the-fruit or “natural”-processed Ethiopia, with both high- and low-toned florals (citrus blossom and fine musk) as the thesis of the cup.
title: Ethiopia Guji Zone Natural

Coffee Origin: Baringo and Nakura Counties, central Kenya
bottom_line: Classic Kenya cup: honey, citrus and spice.
title: Kenya Boma Peaberry

bottom_line: Lovely dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” profile, lush and opulent yet animated and gently bright.
title: Gesha Village Auction Lot 26 Gori Gesha Natural

bottom_line: A light roast develops the delicacy and gentle vivacity of this cleanly understated yet spectacularly aromatic dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” Gesha profile.
title: Gesha Village Lot 76 Nasha Block

bottom_line: Both zesty and richly floral, a dried-in-the-fruit Gesha cup offering an extraordinary range of striking but harmonious aroma and flavor notes.
title: Gesha Village Natural Oma Block Lot 72

bottom_line: A high-toned flowers-and-cocoa version of the Gesha profile, classic, intense and exhilarating.
title: Gesha Village 1931, Lot 86

bottom_line: Crisp yet lush, deep, intricate, a classic Gesha from Hacienda Esmeralda, the ground zero of the Gesha variety’s take-off to fame.
title: Esmeralda Special Auction Washed Geisha

bottom_line: Intensely sweet, intensely roasty, intensely Gesha. And given it’s Gesha, an impressive value.
title: Panama Geisha

bottom_line: The Gesha character exerts a quiet but decisive influence in this classic, sweetly bright and balanced Guatemala.
title: Guatemala Acatenango Gesha

bottom_line: A crisp, resonant wet-processed version of the Gesha profile, simultaneously sweet and tartly drying, with an enriching musky, savory edge.
title: Gesha Village Ethiopia Lot #18 Illubabor Washed

bottom_line: Hints of Gesha complexity contribute resonant intrigue to this classic, gently pungent Guatemala.
title: Guatemala El Injerto Legendary Gesha

bottom_line: Extraordinary shifting and intricate flavor and aroma supported by a flawless structure, classic in its sweet-tart balance.
title: Carmen Geisha El Palomar Best of Panama #4 Carlos Aguilera

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: A lush, resonant dried-in-the-fruit coffee with a brisk edge: a fruit-bomb for grown-ups.
title: Kilenso Ethiopia Natural

Coffee Origin: Mantiqeiras de Minas growing region, Minas Gerais State, Brazil
bottom_line: An accessible, deeply sweet, caramel-toned Brazil cup. Those who avoid aggressive acidity but enjoy a lighter-roasted, very gently bright cup should particularly value this selection.
title: Brazil Paulo Ribeiro Rocha

bottom_line: A rich, complex, rather atypical Colombia coffee that deepens as you linger with the cup: bright but resonant, deeply spice-toned.
title: Colombia Daniel Ortega

bottom_line: A high-toned, elegantly crisp, washed Yirgacheffe cup with a cocoa throughline.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Washed Adado Gr 1

bottom_line: A very distinctive and original Guatemala, fusing sweet/savory depth with delicate, lively nut and floral aromatics.
title: Bella Carmona Guatemala

bottom_line: A discreetly fruit-toned, honey-processed coffee with aromatic wood notes as ballast.
title: Costa Rica La Cereza Roja Semi-Washed

bottom_line: A deeply engaging, sweetly savory Kenya espresso, striking, original yet complete, enticing both as straight shot and in milk.
title: Karuthi Espresso

bottom_line: A compelling espresso as both straight shot and in cappuccino-scaled milk: delicate and deeply rich, with notes of tropical fruit, jasmine and crisp lemon zest.
title: Chelelektu Espresso

bottom_line: A sweet-toned, zesty washed Yirgacheffe coffee that leads with rich floral notes grounded by suggestions of grapefruit zest.
title: Chelelektu Ethiopia

bottom_line: A deeply rich, layered Kenya cup with savory sweetness characteristic of this celebrated origin’s most classic coffees.
title: Karuthi Kenya

bottom_line: The slightly darker roast is felt rather than tasted in this extraordinarily deeply stated, complete version of the great Gesha profile. Those who may enjoy the aromatic extravagance of the Gesha profile but put off by Gesha’s often brightly assertive acidity should particularly value this rounder, yet still exhilaratingly vibrant version.
title: Finca El Obraje Colombia Gesha

bottom_line: A distinct roasty edge complicates this superb Kenya, with its characteristic and engaging tart berry, grapefruit citrus and crisp floral notes.
title: Kenya AA Top Nyeri Tekangu Tegu Microlot

bottom_line: Quiet, elegant Peru, with chocolate and ripe fruit notes rounded and deepened by a very tactful, backgrounded medium-dark roast.
title: Peru Cajamarca Organic

bottom_line: A no-apologies dark roast that retains resonant complexity and vibrant balance throughout the profile.
title: Ethiopia Organic Dark

bottom_line: Crisply sweet roast-toned blend with a pleasing aromatic range: nut and chocolate with delicate stone fruit and floral complication.
title: Chimney Rock Blend

bottom_line: A rich, idiosyncratic version of an already idiosyncratic coffee type, a darker roasted wet-hulled Sumatra. We didn’t register much of the famous Sumatra earth or pipe tobacco, but we did get a big, spicy yet fudgy chocolate and a complex pungent sweetness.
title: Sumatra Tanah Karo

bottom_line: A quiet, accessible darker-roasted coffee, sweet and caramelly with a brisk, zesty edge.
title: Duomo Espresso Northern Italian Style

bottom_line: A twisty version of the ancient Mocha-Java blend, probably quite authentic with its suggestions of wood, spicy nut and chocolate.
title: Mocha Java Blend Fair Trade Organic

Coffee Origin: Yirgacheffe growing region, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: A pungent, intricate darker-roasted Ethiopia Yirgacheffe, lushly floral in front with an engagingly bittersweet, savory-edged depth.
title: Ethiopia Baraka Buna

bottom_line: Unusual juxtaposition of aromatic wood, flowers and cocoa animate a zesty, bittersweet medium-dark-roasted blend.
title: Dreamlands Blend

Coffee Origin: Yirgacheffe growing region, Gedeo Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: A delicate, floral-and-cocoa wet-processed Ethiopia turned richly crisp by a tactful darker roast.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Aricha

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, northern Sumatra, Indonesia
bottom_line: An authentic “forest floor” style of Sumatra coffee brought to a briskly decisive darker roast, enriching without obscuring its pleasing earthy idiosyncrasy.
title: Sumatra Narata Nauli

Coffee Origin: Kochere, Yirgacheffe growing region, south-central Ethiopia
bottom_line: An elegant, crisply high-toned, floral-driven washed Yirgacheffe with a cocoa throughline.
title: Washed Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Banko Gotiti

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Sumatra Province, Sumatra, Indonesia
bottom_line: A classic wet-hulled Sumatra, equal parts floral- and earth-toned, with rich aromatic wood and chocolate notes throughout.
title: Sumatra Danau Toba

bottom_line: An enticing, classic Kenya: bright, juicy, crisp, powerful yet finely balanced.
title: Kapsakiso Kenya

Coffee Origin: Shakiso growing district, Guji Zone, Oromia Region, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: This natural-processed Ethiopia cup is an engaging study in contrasts: sweetly fermenty fruit notes juxtaposed with suggestions of gently scorched aromatic wood.
title: Ethiopia Oromia

Coffee Origin: Kalehe, South Kivu Province, Democratic Republic of the Congo
bottom_line: A crisp, spice-framed Congo natural with suggestions of rich almond notes throughout the profile.
title: Congo Natural

Coffee Origin: Odo Shakiso District, Guji Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: A sumptuous washed Ethiopia cup with absorbing and intricate floral, fruit and chocolate notes throughout.
title: Ethiopia Washed Kayon Mountain

bottom_line: An attractive washed Yirgacheffe, peachy sweet and spicy-savory.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe

bottom_line: A medium-dark roast nicely develops this wet-processed Ethiopia’s chocolate and spice notes. A good choice for those who enjoy strongly stated profiles.
title: Static Ethiopia Konga Washed

bottom_line: An extraordinarily original coffee, both in story (Gesha variety, unorthodox processing) and in its stunning aromatics, both intricately complex, yet grandly and resonantly complete.
title: Ninety Plus Gesha Estates Limited Batch #227

bottom_line: A deeply sweet, spice-inflected blend with pleasing roast notes that suggest cedar.
title: Our Blend Espresso

bottom_line: A crisply high-toned washed Ethiopia coffee offering a fine balance of sweet fruit and aromatic wood notes.
title: Adado Shara Ethiopia Washed

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Sumatra Province, Sumatra, Indonesia
bottom_line: An enigmatic, deep Sumatra cup, with classic layering of lush fruit and foresty notes of tobacco, orchid and fresh earth.
title: Tano Batak Sumatra

bottom_line: A resonantly engaging Kenya cup: smoothly bright acidity, sweet fruit and floral notes and a deep, savory throughline.
title: Makwa Kenya AB

Coffee Origin: Sabanilla de Alajuela growing region, Costa Rica
bottom_line: A balanced, sweet-toned Costa Rica cup with a spicy floral notes thorughout.
title: Calle San Juan Costa Rica Honey

Coffee Origin: Odo Shakiso District, Guji Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: A sweet-toned natural Ethiopia cup with elegantly engaging floral and dried fruit notes.
title: Ethiopia Kayon Mountain Natural

bottom_line: A crisply sweet, brisk cup that is wood-framed with gentle fruit and floral complications throughout.
title: Honey-Processed Coffee

bottom_line: A deeply engaging floral-toned Colombia cup with suggestions of chocolate and succulent stone fruit throughout, as well as hints of savory spice.
title: Finca El Guamo Colombia

Coffee Origin: Kalehe, South Kivu Province, Democratic Republic of the Congo
Roaster Location: Kalehe, South Kivu Province, Democratic Republic of the Congo
bottom_line: Chocolate, flower and black pepper notes carry pleasingly through this sweetly rich Congo cup.
title: Congo Lake Kivu Kavisa Bourbon

Coffee Origin: Odo Shakiso District, Guji Zone, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: An intense, delicately rich dried-in-the-fruit, natural-processed Ethiopia cup, with an invitingly sweet-tart structure.
title: Ethiopia Natural Guji Kayon Mountain

bottom_line: A tactful darker-roasted coffee with deep chocolate notes throughout, complicated by raisin and sweet floral hints.
title: Kolombian

bottom_line: A particularly deep-toned version of Kenya’s characteristic style of sweet-tart fruit and lively, bright acidity.
title: Kenya Ndaroini AA

bottom_line: Another compelling Aida Batlle coffee from her El Salvador farm, with deep fruit and cocoa tones and spicy floral notes throughout.
title: El Salvador Finca Kilimanjaro Natural

bottom_line: A crisp, refreshing Rwanda coffee with deep sweetness and hints of savory spice.
title: Gitesi Rwanda

Coffee Origin: Murang’a Foothills, Aberdare Ridge, Central Province, Kenya
bottom_line: Complex, intensely pungent, deeply sweet-savory. Concord grape, honey, marjoram, narcissus, blood orange zest in aroma and cup. Juicy, engaging acidity; plush, syrupy mouthfeel. The resonant, long, flavor-laden finish sustains all of the notes from the cup plus a cinnamon-like hint of spice.
title: Kamagogo Kenya

bottom_line: A compelling, cocoa- and floral-toned espresso with spice notes throughout, both in the straight shot and in milk.
title: Twisted 4.0 Espresso

bottom_line: The originality of this sweetly intricate, multilayered cup is doubtless owing both to a distinguished tree variety – Kenya’s famous SL28 – as well as to an innovative processing wrinkle involving conducting the fermentation step in an infusion of cascara, or the dried husk of the coffee fruit.
title: El Salvador Finca Kilimanjaro Cascara Fermentation Aida Batlle

bottom_line: A sweet, floral-toned Rwanda cup with ballast from tart citrus and savory aromatic wood notes.
title: Rwanda Nyampinga

bottom_line: An accessible, sweet-toned Rwanda coffee saturated with spicy floral complication.
title: Jarama Rwanda

bottom_line: An accessible, balanced, crisply sweet cup offering quiet aromatic surprises.
title: El Salvador La Loma Gloria Washed

Coffee Origin: Ka’u growing region, Big Island of Hawaii
bottom_line: A dried-in-the-fruit or natural cup that engages by way of sweet florals and appealing tart fruit notes.
title: Ka’u Natural Typica

bottom_line: Blueberry central! A fruit-toned natural cup that paradoxically conjures sherry-like wine enveloped in dark chocolate.
title: Loma La Gloria Natural

bottom_line: A complex Rwanda cup that rewards patience with an unfolding of sweet fruit and floral notes juxtaposed with suggestions of savory herbs.
title: Rwanda Twongere Umusaruro

bottom_line: Poised between rich sweetness and bold savory tones, this Kenya is refined and deeply satisfying.
title: Kenya Nyeri Kiamaina PB

bottom_line: A Rwanda tactfully roasted to the dark edge of medium; chocolate-centered with floral and spice notes complicated by a hint of smoky aromatic wood.
title: Rwanda Nyampinga

bottom_line: An inviting dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” coffee from El Salvador, crisply spice-toned and fruit-forward.
title: Montaña de Abi Anny Ruth El Salvador

Coffee Origin: Kalehe, South Kivu Province, Democratic Republic of the Congo
bottom_line: An intriguing Congo cup from a cooperative that is leading the recovery of the Kivu region from civil war, and a sensory gift for those who enjoy savory-leaning coffees complicated and deepened by berry and citrus notes.
title: Congo Muungano

bottom_line: An almost shockingly original Gesha cup, intense, surprising and intricate in its layered aromatics, brisk yet sweet in structure.
title: Colombia La Palma Y El Tucan Gesha

Coffee Origin: Puna District, Big Island of Hawaii
bottom_line: A natural-processed coffee that exhibits grace and finesse in its fruit-forward elegance.
title: Puna Natural

bottom_line: A classic and inviting Central America cup: crisp, sweet, balanced, plush.
title: El Salvador Anny Ruth Red Honey

bottom_line: An accessible, high-toned coffee with inviting pear, vanilla-like florals and aromatic wood notes.
title: Static Tio Emilio Pichincha Ecuador

bottom_line: A solid espresso with a throughline of dark chocolate and citrus zest. Especially compelling in milk, where chocolate notes intensify, supported by vanilla-like floral tones.
title: Selected Medium Roast Espresso

bottom_line: An accessible, rich, chocolate-toned espresso with hints of orange zest throughout.
title: Selected Full City Roast Espresso

Coffee Origin: Holualoa, North Kona growing district, “Big Island” of Hawaii
bottom_line: Unusual, pleasing and wide-ranging in aroma and flavor, from chocolate to citrus blossom and savory spice to hints of tropical fruit.
title: Bourbon Peaberry

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing region, North Sumatra Province, Sumatra, Indonesia
bottom_line: A flavor-saturated Sumatra with lively citrus, elegant fruit and lush tobacco notes.
title: Sumatra Boru Batak

bottom_line: An appealing Kenya cup, driven by berry and spice notes and vanilla-like florals.
title: Kenya Marumi AA

bottom_line: A sweetly pungent, complex, floral-toned shot; in milk, chocolate-laden with suggestions of coconut.
title: Competition Espresso

bottom_line: An appealing blend for those who value a sweet, roast-toned straight shot that is softened and enlivened in cappuccino-sized milk.
title: Espresso Blend #01 Full City Roast

bottom_line: An original Burundi coffee, unusual both for its processing method (dried-in-the-fruit or natural; most Burundi coffee is wet-processed or washed) and its striking floral-toned acidity.
title: Burundi Kayanza Kabuye Mpanga Natural

bottom_line: Satisfying chocolate and nut notes nearly carry the day in this briskly bittersweet coffee from Puerto Rico.
title: 100% Arabica Coffee from Puerto Rico

bottom_line: An elegant washed Gesha from Ethiopia: juicy, delicately intense, flower-driven.
title: Gesha Village Estate Bench Maji Gesha G1

bottom_line: A deep, sweet-savory Colombia cup with inviting chocolate and tart-fruit notes.
title: Pink Bourbon Colombia Cauca

bottom_line: Not a conventional coffee profile, but a striking one. The influence of the whiskey-casking dominates, but lushly, complexly, rather originally.
title: Barrel Proof

bottom_line: This very sensitively light-roasted coffee offers a delicate, refreshing take on spirits barrel-conditioned coffee.
title: Barrel-Aged Coffee

bottom_line: This complex expression of delicate but powerfully aromatic green coffee, a hint of wine-toned alcohol and distinct roast notes should please those who like a roasty but nuanced and original cup.
title: Wine-Barrel-Aged Ethiopia

bottom_line: A resonant, complexly layered, quite original cup.
title: Bourbon-Barrel-Aged Kenya Baragu

Coffee Origin: Apaneca-Ilamatapec growing region, western El Salvador
bottom_line: Balanced, quietly zesty; the wine gently but explicitly complicates acidity and flavor in this graceful El Salvador.

bottom_line: A beverage of contrasts. Lush but crisp in its floral- and cocoa-toned aromatics; sweet but bracingly bitterish and dry in structure. The aromatics prevail in a smooth, refreshing finish.

bottom_line: The great wet-hulled Sumatra profile takes on a particularly graceful resonance in this traditionally aged version.

bottom_line: An expressive espresso blend that unfurls with deep chocolate, sweet floral and tart fruit notes over hints of smoky aromatic wood.
title: Espresso Havana

bottom_line: A sweetly herbaceous, crisp, cocoa-toned Colombia cup.
title: Static Rio Negro Colombia

bottom_line: An accessible, sweetly nut- and spice-toned Brazil cup.
title: Static Santa Luzia Brazil

bottom_line: A bright yet lush straight shot that expresses its complexity with particular conviction in cappuccino-sized milk.
title: Colombia La Palma and El Tucan Espresso

bottom_line: A big-bodied, high-toned, crisply sweet Panama Gesha that resonates with citrus and cocoa notes throughout.
title: Ninety Plus Estate Panama Gesha Lycello

bottom_line: Attractive darker-roasted Costa Rica, pungent and chocolaty with a zesty orange edge.
title: Costa Rica Microlot White Honey

bottom_line: Crisply roasty, while maintaining plush body and an attractive set of fruit, chocolate and floral notes.
title: Hopper Blend Espresso

bottom_line: A straightforward cup with an appealing throughline of sweet nut and fruit tones and gentle acidity.
title: Peru Rayos del Sol Single Farm

bottom_line: A crisply sweet, ripe-berry-driven Yirgacheffe cup with attractive chocolate tones throughout.
title: Ethiopia Tawo Mok

bottom_line: An engaging espresso blend for its sweet floral and crisp fruit tones, all ensconced in notes of dark chocolate that develop with particular appeal in milk.
title: Dharma Blend Espresso

bottom_line: A powerhouse Ethiopia espresso blend with a floral-tart composure that maintains its complexity and intensity in both straight shot and milk.
title: Flight Seasonal Espresso

bottom_line: A commanding Kenya coffee: sophisticated yet playful, with tropical fruit and sweet floral tones in harmonious balance.
title: Kenya Kabare AA

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia
bottom_line: An essentially sweet natural Sidamo cup with savory depth and a crisp, spice-toned throughline.
title: Ethiopia Sidamo Mulish

bottom_line: For those who enjoy the virtues of decidedly light-roasted coffees, this Peru offers a delicately floral cup with high-toned cacao notes throughout.
title: Milepost Peru Rayos del Sol

bottom_line: A lovely breakfast-style blend with gentle ripe-fruit tones (the honey-processed coffees in the blend?) animated by a sweetly tart vivacity.
title: Three Pillars Blend

bottom_line: A delightfully balanced Costa Rica cup, classic in its expression of crisp, gentle acidity and ripe fruit and sweet floral notes.
title: Costa Rica Sonoran Estate Red Catuai

Coffee Origin: Matas de Minas growing region, Minas Gerais State, Brazil
bottom_line: A pleasing, accessible cup for those who enjoy mild, sweetly nut- and chocolate-toned Brazils.

bottom_line: A deeply inviting natural Gesha cup, splendidly structured and fulfilling in its range of clean fruit and floral tones sustained from aroma to finish.
title: Gesha, Gesha Village 1931

bottom_line: An enticingly unusual coffee in general, but a classic in the Burundi sense: crisp, simultaneously sweet and savory-tart, as well as high-toned.

Such complications can be generated by serendipitous accidents of fruit removal and drying. We hope, however, that they are related to botanical variety, since this sample was produced from trees of a rare and unusual hybrid developed by Hawaii-based scientist Chifumi Nagai that combines the distinctive-tasting Mokka variety, probably originally from Yemen or Ethiopia via Brazil, and a sturdy local strain of the classic Typica.

bottom_line: Sweetly dry, berry-toned Kenya elegance in a moderately dark-roasted format.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy big, fruity and oaky red wines.

bottom_line: An exceptional and unusual dried-in-the-fruit coffee, with the sweetness and aromatic complexity characteristic of the type expressed cleanly without the distraction of over-the-top fruit. Sweet floral notes and buttery richness carries through a remarkable finish. Richly flavor saturated in two- to four-parts milk with a touch of grapefruit acidity, all of which is buoyantly juxtapositioned with the milky sweetness.

bottom_line: A balanced, comfortable coffee with a plush mouthfeel and flavor notes ranging from pungently crisp to lushly sweet.

Coffee Origin: Caranavi Province, La Paz Department, Bolivia.
bottom_line: Those who enjoy depth, resonance and a juicy rather than bright acidity.

bottom_line: Those who prefer quietly resonant, gently complex coffees.
title: Ecuador Vilcabamba

bottom_line: Those who enjoy crisp, slightly earthy and savory beverages.

bottom_line: Classically rich and crisply chocolate-toned dark roast for Keurig owners.

bottom_line: A quietly balanced, gently nuanced breakfast cup for Keurig owners.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a briskly savory-edged breakfast cup.

title: Kenya Nyeri Karogoto

title: Kenya Microlot AA Kamuchuni

bottom_line: Superb, balanced but intensely aromatic example of the great Yirgacheffe profile.

title: Mexico Santa Teresa BCS 02: Cabernet Franc Barrel

bottom_line: Distinctive aromatics and an essential balance and sweetness should make this an attractive, exciting breakfast cup for almost any one.
title: Yirgacheffe Belekatu

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the richly bright, juicy side of the great Kenya cup.

bottom_line: Fine version of the great Yirgacheffe profile, with an emphasis on delicate sweetness and brisk, complex flowers.

bottom_line: Inspiring story on the bag and crisp, subtle complexity in the cup.
title: Single-Estate Piko’s Peaberry

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a quiet, clean, subtly complex breakfast cup with an inspiring story.
title: Single-Estate Medium

bottom_line: An attractive, complex and balanced alternative for Keurig owners. Maintains character well at a taller ten-ounce brew setting.
title: Monk-Shot Breakfast Blend

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the moist foresty notes of Sumatra Arabica coffees may enjoy this understated variant on the style.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy pungent, rough beverages like retsina wines and mescals.
title: House Blend

bottom_line: Sensory adventurers interested in sampling a decent quality dried-in-the-fruit Robusta.
title: Pure Robusta

bottom_line: Aficionado adventurers curious about this very unusual blend of coffee species, although the impact of dry-processing (drying in the fruit) and a darkish roast may obscure any clear view of the sensory impact of species.
title: Highland Grove

bottom_line: This is a coffee for aficionados curious about this very rare blend of coffee species, although the impact of dry-processing (drying in the fruit) and a darkish roast may obscure any clear view of the sensory impact of species.
title: Festival Blend

bottom_line: Complex, pleasing variation on the chocolate-and-brandy dried-in-the-fruit Yirgacheffe profile and an excellent value.
title: Ethiopia Worka Natural

Coffee Origin: Gomma Woreda, Limu region, southwestern Ethiopia.
bottom_line: Those who enjoy the honeyish, crisply sweet, meadowy character of a very pure washed coffee at a relatively light roast.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a discreetly roast-muted version of the floral- and fruit-toned Ethiopia profile at a very attractive price.
title: 100% Ethiopian

bottom_line: Keurig owners interested in an excellent value Ethiopia coffee that preserves some of the character of the origin in a darker roasted style.
title: 100% Ethiopian (K-Cup)

bottom_line: Those who prefer resonant depth to crisp brightness in a straight shot. Should hold its character well in taller milk drinks.
title: Forbidden Cave of Maya Guatemalan Blend

bottom_line: A brilliant example of the original Gesha profile, for those who can afford it.
title: Mario San Jose Geisha

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a natural, honeyish sweetness and jammy fruit in a very clean dried-in-the-fruit profile.
title: Ethiopia Amaro Gayo

bottom_line: A floral-toned, slightly savory version of the great chocolate-and-brandy southern Ethiopia dried-in-the-fruit profile.

bottom_line: Sweet and floral but delicately dry, should please lovers of Rieslings and similar styles of white table wine.
title: Idido Cooperative Yirgacheffe Ethiopia

bottom_line: Aromatics stretch nicely from earthy base through chocolate to fruit; impressively lively mouthfeel. Maintains presence well in milk.
title: Espresso Blend

Coffee Origin: Yirgacheffe growing region, southern Ethiopia; Brazil; Huila Department, southwestern Colombia.
bottom_line: A sophisticated darker roasted espresso, with the roast contributing some pungent bittersweet character without muting aromatics or thinning an impressively full mouthfeel and substantial presence in milk.
title: Espresso

bottom_line: A soothing but engaging holiday blend that should make a small contribution to peace, on earth and at the dinner table.
title: Summit Winter Blend

bottom_line: Classically please-em-all holiday blend, though aficionados might find this updated version of the ancient Mocha-Java blend interesting for its blend composition. The Java, as it does in the original blend archetype, contributes a rounding base; in this case supporting a gently bright, crisply berry-toned Kenya.
title: Holiday Blend

bottom_line: A versatile, drinkable holiday blend with attractive social and environmental credentials at a very attractive price.
title: Holiday Blend

bottom_line: Subtle authority and gentle sweetness; excellent holiday value.
title: Fa-La-La-La-La

Coffee Origin: San Agustín growing region, Huila Department, southern Colombia
bottom_line: A pure, deep-toned, full-bodied cup in the classic Colombia style. Produced from trees of the Caturra variety, a selection of Bourbon that is usually rather basic in the cup, but that here displays some of the celebrated pungent berry character of its parent.
title: Colombia San Agustin Arnulfo Leguizamo

bottom_line: Not a holiday blend, but a felicitous choice of single-origin coffee that expresses an appropriately winter holiday sensory theme of fruit, chocolate and pleasingly pungent aromatic wood.
title: Original Christmas (SO Yirgacheffe)

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
bottom_line: Superb version of the Ethiopian dried-in-the-fruit or “natural” profile, with the complex, juicy sweetness of the type expressed with unusual purity and vivacity.
title: Ethiopia Nekisse

bottom_line: Certainly the sweetest, and probably the best, Rwanda we have sampled for some time. The sweetness is the natural kind, a deeply nuanced expression of orchard-like purity enriched by a tactfully caramelizing roast. You certainly don’t need sweetener for this one.
title: Rwanda Abakundakawa

bottom_line: Great depth, range and balance of sensation make this an exceptional choice for any season, any holiday.
title: Jingle Bell Natural Yirgacheffe

bottom_line: As refreshing and heady as a tropical morning, a cliché that seems absolutely justified by this light, levitating version of the rare Gesha variety. Buy it close to when you’re going to drink it, and if you give it, make sure it doesn’t sit in the gift pile too long.
title: Panama La Esmeralda Especial

bottom_line: Simply a superb, complete coffee; the great Kenya style at its finest.
title: Kenya Kamviu

bottom_line: A light but fully developed roast foregrounds an extraordinary version of a very rare coffee. If you splurge on it for the holidays do your splurging close to when you are planning to drink the coffee, brew it carefully, and leave the sweetener on the counter and the dairy in the fridge.
title: Panama Don Pachi Natural Geisha

bottom_line: Anyone who can afford it. An amazing coffee.
title: Perci Red Panama Gesha

bottom_line: Aficionados interested in enjoying the deep, low-toned, savory fruit tendencies of the Pacamara variety.
title: Guatemala El Injerto Pandora Del Carmen Pacamara

bottom_line: Those who understand and appreciate a classically bright coffee. There is nothing sour, bitter or astringent here; instead a lushly sweet-toned, flavor-nuanced tart sensation vibrates at the heart of the profile.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy roundly rich, syrupy espressos.
title: Gentle Hades

bottom_line: Those who enjoy zesty, brisk espressos.
title: Lightning Athena

Coffee Origin: Wahgi Valley, Western Highlands, Papua New Guinea.
bottom_line: Those who enjoy the quietly exotic.
title: Papua New Guinea Kimel

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a pleasing balance of tart fruit and oaky chocolate in straight shot and milk.

bottom_line: An aficionado’s dried-in-the-fruit coffee with the brandy-like appeal of the type complicated by hints of clove and sandalwood.

bottom_line: I can’t call a coffee this expensive a bargain, but it is less expensive than the more celebrated Panama Geshas, and given its extraordinary complexity and character, an excellent value for those who appreciate and can afford the genuinely exceptional.
title: Colombia La Esperanza Cerro Azul Geisha

Coffee Origin: Valle del Cauca growing region, Colombia.
bottom_line: A balanced, elegant version of the extravagantly aromatic Gesha profile.

bottom_line: The crisply sweet berry character of great Kenyas shows up here in this very distinctive, resonantly elegant profile.

bottom_line: Deep, whisky-and-honey aromatic character may make this cup a particularly good afternoon or evening choice.

bottom_line: Delicately complex, sweet, very slightly savory, a subtly unusual profile for subtle palates.
title: Finca El Socorro Maracaturra, Guatemala

bottom_line: For K-cuppers an unusual opportunity to sample one of the world’s most celebrated (and expensive) coffees, the Gesha variety of Arabica. A nice gift for the K-cup aficionado.
title: Colombia Geisha (K-Cup)

bottom_line: A superb espresso, exotic and distinctive both as straight shot and in short milk.

bottom_line: A coffee exhilaratingly exotic in its aromatics yet cleanly articulated and classic in structure.
title: Ethiopia Washed Yirgacheffe Aroma Roast

bottom_line: For those connoisseurs interested in sampling a distinctive single-origin espresso.
title: Kenya Echo

bottom_line: Classic Guatemalan variation on the classic American breakfast cup: sweetly acidy, big-bodied, complex, rich.
title: Guatemala Huehuetenango Finca La Bolsa

bottom_line: A brisk, rather elegant bittersweet character makes this an unusual variation on the great Yirgacheffe profile.
title: Ethiopia Konga

bottom_line: Impressive aromatic range and complexity with pleasing mouthfeel in the straight shot; fades a bit in milk.
title: Mexico Chiapas Phoenix Special S.O. Espresso

bottom_line: Those who enjoy depth and savory sweetness in a versatile espresso.
title: House Blend

bottom_line: Those who enjoy dry, spicy, floral-toned white table wines.
title: Kenya AA

bottom_line: Those who enjoy rich, savory-sweet beverages. Should take whitener well.

bottom_line: Giddily sweet and complex expression of the Gesha cup. If you can afford it, try it.
title: Lycello Panama Gesha

bottom_line: A superb, unapologetic Sumatra of the deep, cleanly and richly earthy style.
title: Sumatra Lintong Blue Batak Peaberry

bottom_line: Exotic, richly brandy-toned cup for coffee adventurers.
title: El Salvador Los Pirineos Natural Red Bourbon

bottom_line: Classic Central American breakfast cup: balanced, juicy, complete.
title: Honduras Maria Galo

bottom_line: Those who prefer red wines and whisky to white wines and vodka.
title: Guatemala San Juan

bottom_line: Lovers of crisply complex, dry white table wines.

bottom_line: Very low price; very, very poor quality by any standard that we know of.
title: Classic Roast

bottom_line: We’ve tasted this brand and this coffee when it was considerably better. Maybe you’ll get lucky with yours.
title: 100% Colombian

bottom_line: Nothing wrong; nothing much right here either except for the very attractive price. A clean but very simple, woody cup.
title: 100% Colombian

bottom_line: Those looking for Starbucks’ version of “mellow and soft” (very) at an attractive price.
title: Veranda Blend Blonde

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a cleanly delicate medium roast at a reasonable price.
title: Breakfast Blend Rainforest Alliance

bottom_line: Decent, balanced dark roast at a very attractive price.
title: House Blend Medium Roast

bottom_line: Peetniks and other dark-roast lovers on a budget.
title: Major Dickason’s Blend

bottom_line: A cigar-and-leather-armchair style coffee, deep and richly brandy-like.
title: Organic Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Amaro Gayo

bottom_line: Classic Kenya: intense, elegant, complex.
title: Karatu Kenya AA

bottom_line: Delicate, lively, silky cup should please palates tuned to subtlety.

bottom_line: A balanced, quietly complex cup with thorough-going socially and environmentally progressive credentials.
title: Guatemala Quetzel

bottom_line: Aficionados or anyone interested in a particularly deep, pungently lush variation on the classic Kenya cup.
title: Kenya Thunguri – Top Auction Lot

bottom_line: Persuasive local cause, nicely balanced cup.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the natural, complex sweetness of roasted cocoa nib in a gently roast-rounded coffee.

bottom_line: A rather rough-edged but vigorous, engaging blend supporting a timely cause with personal resonance at Caribou.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy exhilarating aromatics, a briskly tart structure and grassroots soccer.

bottom_line: Intense but balanced espresso, dynamic in the small cup and suavely complex in short milk.

bottom_line: Aficionados interested in sampling one of the most original and striking dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopian coffees to appear this year.

bottom_line: A fine variation on the classic washed Yirgacheffe profile, with exhilarating lime and lush floral notes.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a straight shot with full but lively mouthfeel and a balanced complexity.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy an espresso that balances tart authority with chocolaty sweetness.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy sensory excitement and surprise.

bottom_line: Those who can handle both intensity and complexity in a striking and unusual coffee.

bottom_line: A contemplative sort of coffee, deep, quiet, sweet without sentiment.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy deep, authoritative, richly stated coffees with a hint of roasty pungency.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy subtle, gentle beverages.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy white wines that are delicate and crisply dry yet sweet.
title: Costa Rica La Candelilla Honey Peaberry

bottom_line: A subtle coffee subtly light-roasted produces a crisply delicate, refreshing cup.

bottom_line: Coffee iconoclasts. Complex and unexpected.

bottom_line: Very sweet, quite tart; those who don’t normally care for tartly acidy coffees may be persuaded by this deep, richly subtle rendition.

bottom_line: Those in pursuit of intensity; a flamboyant and bracing cup.

bottom_line: Not a showy cup, but a quietly complex, quite comfortable one.

bottom_line: A quiet but delicately complex morning cup.
title: Signature Mocha Java

bottom_line: A subtle, floral-toned dark roast for Keurig owners.

bottom_line: A superbly deep and balanced single-origin, straight-shot espresso, with the acidity turned from assertive to roundly rich by a skillful roast.

bottom_line: A quiet but distinctive Yirgacheffe that should please those who like their flowers, citrus and cocoa in balance, present but not insistent.

bottom_line: Sweet but crisp variant on the great Kenya profile.

bottom_line: Lovers both of the old, funky Sumatras as well as the new, more refined (yet still intense) versions like this one.

bottom_line: A gently crisp, floral, refreshing version of the great Kenya profile.

bottom_line: Complex straight shot with an impressive and classic range of sensation.

bottom_line: Balanced and gently complex as straight shot; delicately pleasing in short milk.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the extravagant and uncompromising.

bottom_line: A quietly balanced espresso with good vanilla-toned chocolate character.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a bracingly bright old-fashioned American cup.

bottom_line: Honeyish, meadowy version of the great Gesha profile.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy lighter-roasted coffees with delicately brisk acidity and fresh, meadowy aromatics.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the contrast and excitement of rich, strongly stated acidity enveloped in great natural sweetness complicated by distinctive aromatics.
title: La Minita Peaberry

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a deep-toned, full-bodied espresso with a very discreet dark-roast edge.

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
bottom_line: Those who enjoy light-roasted coffees with brilliantly complex aromatics.

bottom_line: Particularly brisk and complex version of the great Yirgacheffe profile.

bottom_line: A gift to drinkers of decaffeinated espresso: Impressive as a straight shot and even better in short milk.

bottom_line: Intense, dramatic, but refreshingly juicy Ethiopia for those who enjoy excitement at breakfast.

bottom_line: A pleasantly rounded, bittersweet darker-roasted cup with reassuring environmental and social credentials for K-Cup drinkers.

bottom_line: A classic breakfast cup, sweet but brightly acidy.

bottom_line: Smooth and mild flavor as advertised; also depth and balanced richness.

bottom_line: Lovers of complex, challengingly dry white wines.

bottom_line: Balanced, well-structured breakfast blend with simple but attractive aromatics and a pleasing dark chocolate nuance.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy dry but floral/spicy white table wines may particularly enjoy this delicately complex coffee.
title: Burundi Sogestal Mumirwa

bottom_line: Those who enjoy cleanly delicate, sweet-toned beverages.
title: Tanzania Mpito

bottom_line: Comfortable coffee: Brisk but not bright, pleasantly full in mouthfeel.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy fruity/oaky red table wines and dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia coffees.
title: Rwanda Buremera

bottom_line: Gentle acidity and briskly complex aromatics should please those who enjoy fine black teas and lighter bodied, spicy red table wines.

bottom_line: Should please those who enjoy delicately dry, complexly floral white table wines.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a bright, pure but complex morning cup.

bottom_line: Balanced, naturally sweet, quietly but lushly complex.

bottom_line: Lovers of the idiosyncratic. Those who enjoy Islay single-malt whiskies, lapsang souchong teas, heavy beverages that shock and surprise.

bottom_line: Those who like gently suave blends like Illy Caffé but crave just a bit more bite and complexity. A single-origin espresso with impressive balance and completeness.

bottom_line: Simply a perfect expression of the sweet, balanced, quietly complete Kona cup.

title: ChacolaTAY Blend

bottom_line: Lovers of those aperitif and dessert wines that combine fruit notes with herb and aromatic wood.

bottom_line: Lovers of good port wines.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy foods and beverages with unorthodox juxtapositions of taste and flavor: salted plums, for example, stewed fruits, certain mescals and grappas.

bottom_line: Balanced, delicate breakfast cup with light body but refined finish.

bottom_line: Those looking for a juicy, honey-toned morning cup.

bottom_line: Those who prefer subtle but opulent beverages.
title: Brazil Sitio do Tanque

bottom_line: Balanced, gentle, refreshing Brazil, quietly exceptional.

Those whose brewers offer the option of brewing at four ounces will find the Sumatra character more pronounced at the smaller, more concentrated serving size.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a balanced but assertively bright breakfast cup.

bottom_line: Medium-roast drinkers who find themselves out of coffee and close to a Starbucks.

bottom_line: Those who find directness and simplicity a virtue.

bottom_line: A forceful, deep-structured cup, especially when hot.
title: House Blend

bottom_line: Those who prefer a robust, muscular richness to balance.
title: Holler Mountain Organic

bottom_line: A versatile cup with quiet, balanced authority.
title: Cafe Solano

bottom_line: Lovers of fresh, aromatically arresting breakfast coffees.
title: Farm House Organic

bottom_line: Those who enjoy fine white table wines that balance mineral and fruit. An impressive Kenya in the slightly austere, elegant dry berry style.

bottom_line: Robust, dark-chocolaty cup for acidity-avoiders.

bottom_line: A pungently authoritative but cleanly refined Sumatra in a tactfully darker-roasted style.

bottom_line: The combination of sweetness and austere beauty characteristic of the finest Kenyas displays in this exceptional coffee.

bottom_line: Delicate yet rich acidity in a gentle, floral-toned version of the great Kenya profile.
