bottom_line: Overall complexity and balance could make this selection an interesting starter dried-in-the-fruit coffee for purists who are tempted to stray from their clean and classic wet-processed habits.
title: Ethiopia Gedeo Natural Process

bottom_line: An impressively clean, fresh-toned version of the big, complex fruit character associated with dried-in-the-fruit coffees. The subtly distinctive and complex Pacamara varietal character doubtless also contributes to this coffee’s distinction.
title: El Salvado Finca Ayatepeque Natural-Processed Pacamara

bottom_line: Exemplary example of the balanced, round, quietly deep-toned cup for which Nicaragua is particularly admired. Perhaps the finely balanced acidity and complex aromatics can be attributed to the heirloom Bourbon cultivar.
title: Nicaragua Bourbon City Roast

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a pure, soft yet intense, meadowy breakfast cup.
title: Guatemala Hanupu

bottom_line: A lavish and memorable version of this celebrated and still rare coffee variety.
title: Panama Geisha Aroma Roast

bottom_line: Unusual and distinctive profile, with the savory/sweet complexity found in the best of any given year’s Pacamara. Should please both coffee adventurers and purists. Very sensitively roasted.
title: Guatemala Pandora Pacamara Medium-Light Roast

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the sweet and avoid the bitter in coffee and life. A coffee almost shocking in its natural sweetness. This is not the empty sweetness of refined sugar but rather of ripe fruit, floral honey and fresh-cut, aromatic wood.
title: Starlight Blend

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a crisply lush, aromatically complex straight-shot espresso.
title: Garden Espresso Blend

Coffee Origin: Mogiana growing region, Sao Paulo State, south-central Brazil.
bottom_line: Pungent, grapefruit-like fruit and earth-toned aromatic wood make this Brazil rather Sumatra-like, though gentler and more delicate.
title: Medium Roast Yellow Bourbon Pulped Natural

bottom_line: A Colombia of the true, good old school: Pure and brightly acidy yet accessibly syrupy and sweet-toned.
title: Colombia Tolimas

bottom_line: An almost transcendent expression of one of the world’s finest coffee types.
title: Kenya Nyeri AB Gichatha-ini Signature Series

bottom_line: Those who appreciate bright, somewhat dry, white table wines. Also an interesting change of pace for those who take their espresso with frothed milk; carries its distinctive profile with some authority even into tallish milk.
title: Kenya AA Nyeri Ndiaini Espresso

Coffee Origin: Harrar region of eastern Ethiopia; east Java, Indonesia.
bottom_line: Those looking for excitement. Almost startling intensity and complexity in this unusually clean, bright Harrar.
title: Ethiopia Harrar

bottom_line: A profile as complex and complete as a good blend yet still distinctively Ethiopian.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Koke Coop FTO

bottom_line: A complex straight shot that translates well in short milk drinks.
title: Guatemala Quiche Chajulense FTO Espresso

bottom_line: Only masochists. Our November 2011 supermarket sampling suggests better Robusta-heavy nationally branded canned blends are available at a comparable price.
title: Special Roast

bottom_line: For the curious, an object lesson in how bad a coffee can get if it fails to be developed in the roast. Could perhaps be seen as a botched exercise in anti-Starbuckism, a coffee as raw and woody as many Starbucks coffees are close to burned.
title: Premium Drip Coffee

bottom_line: The organic seal is impressive even though the cup isn’t.
title: Organic Premium

bottom_line: A particularly bad dark-roasted Colombia at the tail end of a bad year for Colombias generally.
title: 100% Colombian

bottom_line: Least offensive of the canned Robusta-centered supermarket blends tested for our November 2011 cupping.
title: House Blend

bottom_line: Except in the aroma, provides little of the pungent, charred intensity buyers of this ultimately dark-roasted coffee type love. Locally produced French roasts are likely to deliver considerably more.
title: French Roast

bottom_line: Once past the aroma not much here. A whole-bean version of this blend bought from a Starbucks store doubtless would maintain more of the initially pleasing aromatics.
title: Africa Kitamu

bottom_line: A smooth, quietly nuanced darker roasted coffee in a roast-and-ground canned format.
title: Dark Roast Rainforest Alliance Certified

bottom_line: Lovers of very delicate drip coffee.
title: Medium Roast Ground

bottom_line: A nicely balanced darker roasted cup at a value price.
title: Dunkin’ Dark

bottom_line: Those on a budget looking for a modest, balanced rendition of a classic American breakfast cup.
title: Original Blend

bottom_line: Those who appreciate a syrupy-sweet straight espresso and cappuccino-sized milk drinks.
title: Twisted

bottom_line: Aficionados of single-origin espressos as straight shots and in short milk. Crisp and quietly complex.
title: Guatemala Alotenango La Candelaria Espresso

bottom_line: A strong-charactered Northern Italian styled espresso that should work well in milk drinks of any size.
title: 100% Arabica 100% Italiano

bottom_line: An almost transcendently classic coffee in the depth and range of its sensation, intense yet balanced.
title: Panama Elida Estate

bottom_line: Those who have learned to enjoy lighter-roasted coffees that bring the freshness of the coffee flower and fruit to the cup.
title: El Salvador Nombre de Dios

bottom_line: This dramatic expression of the citrus and floral Ethiopia cup should please those who enjoy spicy, complex dry white table wines.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Kochere

bottom_line: Lovers of bright, delicate white table wines and coffee drinkers who enjoy the citrus and floral character of washed Ethiopia Yirgacheffe coffees.
title: Colombia Finca San Luis Organic

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a bright but balanced, intensely fragrant breakfast cup.
title: Guatemala El Injerto

bottom_line: Rusty and hearty but balanced and complex. The pungent, earthy fruit character of Indonesia coffees is particularly nicely framed by a moderately dark roast.
title: Reindeer Blend

bottom_line: Fine example of a dried-in-the-fruit coffee, lushly yet freshly fruit-toned.
title: Panama Elida Estate Natural Process

bottom_line: A fine coffee for anyone or any occasion, but aficionados may particularly enjoy attempting to pick out the interwoven contributions of the three processing methods. The brandyish dried-in-the-fruit component is easiest to detect.
title: Panama Elida: The Seasonal Tripel

bottom_line: An aficionado’s dried-in-the-fruit coffee, brought to a light roast that foregrounds a just-picked, meadowy freshness and an unusual purity in the sweetly fermenty fruit notes.
title: Bali Kintamani Organic Rainforest Alliance

Coffee Origin: Guji Zone, Oromia Region, Sidama Province, Ethiopia.
bottom_line: A dried-in-the-fruit coffee with rugged presence and big body that should please those who enjoy slightly edgy spirits: peaty single malts, the more rustic tequilas.
title: Ethiopia Sidamo Ardi

bottom_line: Extravagant, high-toned and intense; should particularly please lovers of dry, spicy white table wines and perfumy gins.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Kochere Micro-lot

bottom_line: Surprisingly fruity for its darkish roast level; should hold up very well in latte-sized milk drinks.
title: Espresso Havana

Coffee Origin: Ethiopia; Guatemala; Brazil; Burundi; Sumatra, Indonesia.
bottom_line: Those who enjoy resonantly deep, slightly carnal fruit in straight espresso. Roundly authoritative in short milk.
title: The Journey Espresso Blend

Coffee Origin: Mae Suay, Chiang Rai, northern Thailand
bottom_line: A versatile straight-shot espresso, with buttery body and bittersweet complexity, but perhaps at its best in short milk, where it maintains its individuality with richness and clarity.
title: Bluekoff Single Origin Thai Espresso Blend (A4+A5)

bottom_line: Richness and complexity in a darker roasted classic coffee.
title: Costa Rica Tarrazu Montecielo

bottom_line: Although a light roast in indicated on the packaging, by international standards this is a medium-dark roast, appealing to those who enjoy the slightly smoky, chocolaty character applied to a fine high-grown coffee by medium-dark roasting.
title: Costa Rica Export Reserve, Light Roast

bottom_line: Well-balanced and distinctive with the complexity of the best Kenya coffees - 95 points, October 2011.
title: Kenya Karinga

bottom_line: The aromatic fireworks of a fine dried-in-the-fruit Ethiopia with none of the fermenty downside. Splendid coffee.
title: Ethiopia Sidamo Guji

bottom_line: The Sumatra earth and fruit character is a bit over the top here but most people who buy Sumatras are looking for energy over elegance anyhow.
title: Sumatra Mandheling Fair Trade Organic

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the fruity, brandy-like (or port-wine-like perhaps) character typical of many dried-in-the-fruit coffees. Not a purist’s coffee - 89 points, October 2011.
title: Organic Guatemla Finca Santa Isabel Natural Process

bottom_line: A dried-in-the-fruit coffee that walks on the wild side, with a fermenty, alcoholic sweetness that conveys considerable complexity as well as a faint overripe, composty shadow.
title: Organic Bali Kintamani Highlands

bottom_line: A darkish, roast-influenced rendition of the classic Ethiopia Yirgacheffe fruit and flowers profile.
title: Resiprocate FTO Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Medium Roast

bottom_line: This naturally sweet coffee with its gentle acidity should please those who take their coffee black and find bright, acidy coffees too assertive and uncomfortable.
title: Organic El Salvador Las Lajas

bottom_line: A style of coffee we used to call “after-dinner,” meaning it embodies an arm-chair-and-brandy sort of richness and authority.
title: Organic Ethiopia Gedeo Worka (Natural-Processed)

Coffee Origin: Sidama (also Sidamo) growing region, southern Ethiopia.
bottom_line: Those coffee drinkers who avoid aggressive acidity and enjoy dark chocolate and nut nuance.
title: Ethiopia Sidamo Oromia FTO

bottom_line: Classic in its bright acidity; unusual in its rather deep, peach-and-melon fruit.
title: Costa Rica Finca Santa Lucia Organic

bottom_line: Lovers of red table wines that pleasingly balance fruit and oak.
title: Guatemala Quiche Chajulense Fair Trade Organic

bottom_line: Pure, crisply floral and citrus wet-processed Ethiopia of the classic style with Fair-Trade/organic credentials.
title: Ethiopia Sidama Union Fair Trade Organic

bottom_line: Quietly distinctive Yirgacheffe should please lovers of classic coffees without alarming them with excessive aromatic fireworks.
title: Café Tierra Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Fair Trade Organic

bottom_line: Those who want difference and drama in their cup.
title: Organic Ethiopia Worka Coop Natural Process

bottom_line: Naturally sweet but crisply nuanced, a coffee for lovers of soft, subtly complex white table wines.
title: Organic Costa Rica Las Lajas Natural Process

bottom_line: One of the world’s most distinctive origins in a darker-roasted mode.
title: Estate of Kenya

bottom_line: Subtle palates that appreciate a pleasing balance of sweeter chocolate-related notes and gently tart fruit in straight shot or short milk.
title: Honduras El Cielito Single Origin Espresso

Coffee Origin: Limmu Kossa District, Jimma Zone, Oromia State, Ethiopia
bottom_line: Lovers of sophisticated, high-cacao chocolates. Complex in the small cup, masterful in milk.
title: Ethiopia Nigusie Lemma Natural Processed Single Origin Espresso

bottom_line: Brightly complex and elegant straight shot that maintains character in short milk and should sustain presence in taller milk beverages as well.
title: Guatemala Santa Isabel Natural Process SO Espresso

bottom_line: Solidly satisfying breakfast cup with a quiet, tartly rich complexity associated with cultivars derived from the heirloom Bourbon variety of Arabica, in this case, Pacas.
title: Honduras Santa Barbara

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the earthy coffees of Sumatra and Sulawesi should enjoy this distinctive variation on the style from Ethiopia.
title: Ethiopia Natural Sidamo Korate Gr. 3 Organic

bottom_line: Refreshing coffee; think the sweet, pink sort of grapefruit with deepening resonances of cedar and dark chocolate.
title: Kenya Gichathaini

bottom_line: An acidity-lover’s coffee for sure, its grandly expressed brightness intensified by an unusually light roast.
title: Kenya Gichathaini

bottom_line: Lovers of big, fruity red table wines and those coffee drinkers who already know they enjoy the lushly fruit- and brandy-toned character of a lightly fermented dried-in-the-fruit “natural” coffee.
title: Kenya Thika Chania Estate Natural Process

bottom_line: An almost creamily smooth mouthfeel and quiet, relatively restrained acidity makes this a particularly accessible rendition of the celebrated Kenya profile.
title: Kenya AA Kangocho

bottom_line: Those who prefer the delicately refreshing possibilities of the Kenya profile.
title: Kenya AA Karogoto Microlot

bottom_line: Intense but sweetly nuanced acidity should please those who enjoy a bright but engagingly complex cup.
title: Kenya Kangocho Full Flavor Roast

bottom_line: The Kenya acidity is enveloped in rich, brandyish fruit and cocoa notes, making this a Kenya for lovers of fruit-rich red table wines.
title: Kenya Karatu-Thika

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a bracing, complex acidy sensation without a hint of sour bite; the acidity is wine-like and nuanced with pungent cedar and lush night flowers.
title: Kenya Tekangu Ngunguru

bottom_line: A slightly bitterish but pleasing bite gives authority to this richly classic Kenya with its spicy floral and pungent berry notes.
title: Kenya Thiriku

bottom_line: Distinctive Kenya fruit in a superbly balanced, versatile cup.
title: Kenya AA Kiaora Estate Full City Roast

bottom_line: A balanced and complete medium-roasted cup, yet remarkable in its aromatic detail.
title: Kenya Giakanja

bottom_line: A brightly acidy coffee with complete and seductive balance and delicately distinctive, layered Kenya aromatics.
title: Kenya Karatu AA

bottom_line: A distinctive and intense yet balanced expression of the pungent/sweet fruit-toned Kenya character.
title: Kenya Kiandu

bottom_line: Lovers of bright, dry white wines and coffee lovers interested in an engaging variation on the classic Kenya profile.
title: Kenya Ruthagati

bottom_line: An unusual pairing of the rare and distinctive-tasting Gesha variety of Arabica with an unorthodox dried-in-the-fruit processing nets a striking and exotic cup, rich, syrupy, savory-sweet.
title: Panama Mama Cata Natural Process Geisha

bottom_line: Balanced Latin-American-style breakfast cup, sweetly crisp and fruit-toned with a hint of savory depth and solid social and environmental credentials.
title: La Union Mexico Fair Trade Organic

bottom_line: Heavy body and rich acidity in particular should help flavor pair with sweetener and/or whitener.
title: Original Roast

bottom_line: Superb straight-shot espresso, smoothly balanced yet lively in detail. Loses its balance a bit in short milk but should power through considerable dairy in taller drinks.
title: Kenya Kirinyaga Kii Peaberry Espresso

bottom_line: Presumably the influence of the Bourbon cultivar gives the fruit its pungent, roundly tart, raisiny richness here. Should please those who enjoy red table wines with dry, complex fruit character.
title: El Salvador Amarillo Yellow Bourbon

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the natural complexities of pure, high-end chocolates.
title: El Salvador Los Alpes El Banco Pacamara Espresso

bottom_line: Wonderfully summery breakfast cup.
title: Guatemala Finca La Candelaria

bottom_line: Nice range of expression in the small cup, from peach-toned flowers to pungent cedar. Strong presence in two parts milk suggests it will hold its own in caffè-latte-scale beverages.
title: Dharma Blend Espresso

bottom_line: Those who enjoy sensory distinction without acidy drama.
title: El Salvador Finca Los Alpes Tierra Fertil Pacamara

bottom_line: Lovers of decisively dry but complexly aromatic white table wines should enjoy this very light-roasted coffee.
title: El Salvador Finca Los Alpes El Banco Pacamara

bottom_line: Syrupy, deep straight shot; should make its presence felt in larger, caffè latte quantities of milk.
title: Bard 2.2 (espresso)

bottom_line: Superb, sweetly earthy, resoundingly complex Sumatra for those who already love Sumatras and want to move up, or those who have never sampled the type and want to at its best.
title: Sumatra Lake Tawar

bottom_line: Nicely balances the deep, rustic fruit of classic Indonesia coffees with a brighter Central America.
title: Bard 2.2

bottom_line: Those whose associations with autumn include the sweetly pungent, slightly smoky, deep, resonant.
title: Hojas de Otono

Coffee Origin: San Agustín growing region, Huila Department, southern Colombia
bottom_line: Those who want to enjoy the assertively acidy but balanced and complexly nuanced cup that impresses international juries.
title: Colombia Cup of Excellence 2011 First Place Winner

bottom_line: Low-toned complexity, smoothly lively mouthfeel and easy, approachable acidity should make this a comfortable but engaging breakfast cup.
title: Costa Rica Las Lajas Honey Process

bottom_line: Superb straight-shot and short-milk espresso: big-bodied, complex but balanced. In tall milk retains flavor though a little light on presence.
title: Espresso Nuevo

bottom_line: Its crisp, pungent brightness and sweet floral notes make it more trendy contemporary American than Italian, and the better for it.
title: Espresso Classico

bottom_line: Pronounced but balanced acidity and complex, harmonious aromatics in a classic medium-roasted Antigua.
title: Guatemalan Puerta Verde

Coffee Origin: Lintong growing district, northern Sumatra, Indonesia.
bottom_line: A superb Sumatra; a wonderful introduction to this unorthodox type for those who don’t know it and a revelation for those who only know the sharply musty variety.
title: Sumatra Lintong

bottom_line: Bright, sweetly acidy and resoundingly complex straight shot; sweet and gently chocolaty in short milk. Not a caffè latte or long milk espresso.
title: Costa Rica Santa Elena Espresso

bottom_line: This unusual coffee should please those who find many admired coffees too acidy and intense, but who still enjoy distinction and originality.
title: Ethiopia Amaro Dernaye

bottom_line: Those who enjoy simple, full-bodied, balanced darker roasts.
title: Nicaragua Cafe Alden

bottom_line: Those who prefer quiet depth to bright acidity with a bonus of impressive social and environmental credentials.
title: Nicaragua Flor de Jinotega FTO

bottom_line: A bit of a cigars-and-brandy style cup, deep, sweet but savory.
title: Nicaragua Finca El Limoncillo Red Pacamara

bottom_line: Those who enjoy grandly acidy, big-bodied medium-roasted coffees.
title: Nicaragua Santa Teresa

bottom_line: Light roasting develops the floral sweetness of this pure and delicate coffee.
title: Nicaragua 5 de Junio Maragojipe

bottom_line: Both those who have never sampled a brandyish, fruity style natural coffee or those who have and love them.
title: Mierisch Farms Pacamara Natural Process

bottom_line: Those who prefer balance to intensity; smooth is perhaps the most overused word in beverage description, but this coffee defines it.
title: Nicaragua Wiwili Organic Micro Lot

bottom_line: Exemplary Nicaragua: rich, robust, deep-toned.
title: Nicaragua SHG

bottom_line: Crisp, cleanly bright breakfast cup with a complicating hint of East Africa.
title: Kenya Kagumo PB Special Reserve Micro Lot

bottom_line: A grandly classic Latin-American cup: powerful but nuanced acidity, full mouthfeel, deeply expressed aromatics.
title: Costa Rica Micro Lot “Pepe” Honey Processed

bottom_line: Those who enjoy sensory depth and quiet authority. Rich and balanced when taken black, but should handle whitener well.
title: Costa Rica Finca Las Gravileas Fair Trade Organic

bottom_line: Clarity and balance in a crisp morning cup.
title: Costa Rica Finca Las Palomas

bottom_line: The pungent Kenya fruit notes are high-toned and complex and the mouthfeel silky in this crisply balanced version of the Kenya profile.
title: Kenya Gichatha-Ini

bottom_line: The pungent Kenya fruit is gently deepened by the roast, rounding complexity and softening acidity.
title: Kenya Gichatha-Ini

bottom_line: The pungent Kenya fruit is softened and deepened without loss of its tart authority in this quietly complex version of the Kenya profile.
title: Kenya Gichatha-Ini

bottom_line: Delicately pure coffee, light-roasted to develop fresh, orchard-like aromatics and natural sweetness. Excellent environmental and social credentials.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Koke Coop Fair Trade Organic

bottom_line: Crisp, sweet-toned lighter-roasted coffee with fine floral notes and excellent environmental and social credentials.
title: Nicaragua Cinco De Junio Fair Trade Organic

bottom_line: Coffee lovers with who don’t mind dropping significant money on a memorable version of the rare and celebrated Gesha profile

bottom_line: Elegantly pungent and earthy, a good choice for those who enjoy fine Sumatras.
title: Rwanda Coopac

bottom_line: An extraordinary coffee, subtle yet exotic, complete.
title: Guatemala Xeucalvitz

bottom_line: Those in quest of the quiet, resonant side of the celebrated Kenya profile.
title: Kenya “Karie” Micro-lot

bottom_line: Deep, tartly rich cup should please those who enjoy dry, complex red table wines.
title: Guatemala Guaya’b

Coffee Origin: El Quiche Department, south central Guatemala
bottom_line: Distinctive straight-shot espresso, pungently fruit-toned and deep.
title: Guatemala Xeucalvitz Espresso

bottom_line: Those who enjoy intense, challenging, strong-charactered beverages.
title: Rwanda Musasa

bottom_line: Classically bright and balanced breakfast cup with impressive social and environmental credentials.
title: Mexico Chiapas Fair Trade

bottom_line: Lovers of dark roasts that combine crisp, roasty character with a full range of flavor and aromatics.

bottom_line: A fine, balanced Yirgacheffe with muted aromatics. A good choice perhaps for those who find the lemon and flowers of most Yirgacheffes too brightly distracting and who may prefer a quieter, rounder version of the type with a fuller, more syrupy feel on the palate.

bottom_line: Dark-roast Sumatra lovers, of which there are many. This version has less musty-earthiness and more chocolate than most traditional Sumatras.
title: Sumatra

bottom_line: Subtle, resonant-finishing Guatemala from a pioneer in sustainable coffee importing, roasting and sales.
title: Organic Guatemalan Medium

bottom_line: A smooth, nut-and-chocolate-toned option for those who avoid brighter, more acidy coffees.
title: Thai Fully City Roast

bottom_line: Those who enjoy classically delicate light-roasted coffees, complex and lively.
title: Honduras Coprocael

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a straightforward, briskly medium-roasted Yirgacheffe cup: silky, floral, lemony.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy complex but dry, challenging white wines.

bottom_line: Those who prefer an Ethiopia that minimizes delicate floral character in favor of crisp, lemony authority.

bottom_line: Quiet authority in a gently complex, cocoa-toned Guatemala.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy dry, delicate, minerally white table wines.

bottom_line: Black coffee drinkers who prefer subtlety to drama.

bottom_line: Balanced, quietly lively cup with a subtlety often associated with Guatemala.

bottom_line: Those who enjoy assertively dry white table wines.

bottom_line: Lovers of dry, brisk, complex morning cups.

bottom_line: Smoothly balanced cup with an inspiring story.

bottom_line: Lovers of White Rieslings and other crisp, floral-toned white table wines.

bottom_line: Deep-toned, unorthodox profile for the single malt and cigar crowd.

bottom_line: Lovers of sweet dessert wines perhaps. Mild ferment (the sugars in the coffee fruit begin to ferment before the removal of the fruit) is technically a taste defect, but many coffee drinkers enjoy mild, wine-like ferment tones when they are sweet and clean, as they are here. The problem with accidental virtues like a fortuitously sweet ferment is that it may not turn up in the next lot of the same coffee.

bottom_line: In the great roulette that Starbucks' mammoth output of coffee has become, those who picked this number were unlucky losers. Spin the wheel again; Starbucks does produce some excellent coffees, as does Yemen.
title: Arabian Mocha Java

Coffee Origin: Northern Sumatra; San Marcos region, northwestern Guatemala.
bottom_line: Those who like the bitter side of bittersweet, with some fruity complication.
title: Casablanca Blend

bottom_line: Those looking for a more complex version of the light-bodied, charred coffees often sold as "French roast."
title: Dark Sumatra

Coffee Origin: Sidamo Province and growing region, southern Ethiopia.
bottom_line: Those palates that find subtlety where others find absence.
title: Ethiopia Sidamos

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the drama of a very dark roast without the typical affliction of charred thinness.
title: French Roast

bottom_line: Those who enjoy macho graphics and complex, fruity dark roasts.
title: Dark Line Red Eye

bottom_line: This versatile dark roast should appeal to those who enjoy dark roasts for their seductive smoothness rather than their macho bitterness.
title: Costa Rica

bottom_line: A classic bittersweet "after dinner" coffee: The bitterish but attractive roastiness is nicely rounded by fruity chocolate.
title: Italian Roast

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the taste of the roast but still want to enjoy the character of a very distinctive origin.
title: Ethiopian Yirgacheffe

bottom_line: Lovers of well-executed examples of the extreme roast style often called "dark French."
title: Oromia Dark Roast, Fair Trade

bottom_line: Coffee-with-milk drinkers, who will find that dairy develops the Harrar fruit tones while rounding and sweetening the cup's underlying bitterness.
title: Ethiopian Harrar

bottom_line: Those who enjoy dark roasts partly for their bitterness, here nicely complicated by a halo of floral and fruit notes.
title: Best of Africa Blend

bottom_line: Dark-roast drinkers who enjoy some fruity complication in a rather demandingly bitter cup.
title: Ethiopia Washed Yirgacheffe Horse

bottom_line: A versatile coffee, with its Yirgacheffe lemon tones and a hint of acidity shimmering in the distinct roast tones.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe Horse

bottom_line: The coffee's distinction is largely lost in the roast, but the roast itself provides the mildly burned, bittersweet cup with a hint of complication that many coffee drinkers enjoy.
title: Ethiopia Limu Fair-Trade

bottom_line: This elegant dark roast coffee, with character and complexity but without bitterness, should appeal to those who drink dark roasts for reasons of pleasure rather than machismo.
title: Kenya AA Nyeri Tatu

bottom_line: Lovers of medium-roasted coffees who feel exiled in the land of dark roasts. Rather subdued for a Yirgacheffe, but in an apparently bad year for Yirgacheffes, this is a good one.
title: Simply Yirgacheffe

bottom_line: This austerely uncompromising Kenya should please those drinkers of traditional breakfast coffees who want something arrestingly different.
title: Kenya Medium Dark Roast

bottom_line: Anyone who wants to know why Kenya is one of the world's premier coffee origins. The acidity is powerful but sufficiently bathed in a natural sweetness that even more timid palates should enjoy this version of the big Kenya profile.
title: Kenya Grand Cru

bottom_line: In marketing terms, this is a polarizing coffee. On the basis of consumer cuppings I have organized, I would guess that most coffee drinkers would object to this coffee, but at least a few would admire its lush, over-the-top strangeness.
title: Mountain Country Viennese Roast

bottom_line: "Past-crop flavor" is a cuppers' term for a dull flatness, often intensified by woody or rope-like tones. The peanut tones Ken objects to probably derive from the very light-roasted component of the blend. However, both Ken and Chris acknowledge this coffee's foreground rich complexity, whether described as wine (Chris) or dry chocolate (Ken).
title: Old City Blend

bottom_line: If this coffee were available in the States, armchair tiebreakers willing to weigh in on its odd aromatic bouquet, which some professionals might label defective and others might accept, or even celebrate, as exotically interesting.
title: India S795

bottom_line: Ken's reading emphasizes the bitter edge of the cup, Chris's the sweet, but either way they are describing a versatile coffee with some exotic complication.
title: India MNEB

bottom_line: If you believe Ken, a quiet, round, versatile coffee with something for everyone. If you believe Chris, drink it fast, enjoy the cup and forget the finish.
title: Mountain Country Indian Kents Plantation A

bottom_line: This heavy-bodied, authoritatively roasty coffee definitely should pull its weight in large quantities of milk.
title: India Dark Roast

bottom_line: Those who will put up with a problematic finish for the sake of an impressively aromatic, big-bodied dark-roast cup.
title: India Full City Roast

bottom_line: Lovers of sweetly dry exotic breakfast coffees looking for a distinguished variant on the theme. I settled on pears and Chris on mandarin orange, but we both admired the same exhilaratingly high-toned, crisp-yet-sweet fruit tones.
title: India Jumboor Estate MNEB

bottom_line: Anyone interested in a style of India cup that makes a deliciously high-toned, fruity reference to the great coffees of East Africa, but remains singularly itself.
title: India Badnekhan Estate

bottom_line: An agreeable dark roast for caffeine-avoiders, particularly those who take their coffee with milk, which will soften the profile and make it to fatten and blossom.
title: Capricorn Blend Decaffeinated

bottom_line: Lovers of the old, hearty Starbucks dark-roast Sumatra cup will find this coffee a reasonably persuasive caffeine-free variation.
title: Decaf Sumatra

bottom_line: Outside the cup immaculately correct; in the cup understated enough to enjoy black but robust enough to handle quantities of milk.
title: Fair Trade Decaf Blend

bottom_line: A versatile coffee whose sturdy but expansive character when cool should make it particularly fine as a darker-roasted summer beverage taken over ice.
title: Decaf Skye’s Mountain Blend

bottom_line: This organic coffee's roasty, rounded power should carry through large quantities of milk.
title: Decaf Mexico Organic

bottom_line: I could say lovers of Reese's Peanutbutter Cups, but that would misrepresent a sophisticated, unusual and refreshing coffee.
title: Decaf Louisiana Blend Medium Dark

bottom_line: The quintessential romantic's coffee, glamorous both in history and cup.
title: Decaf Mocca Java

bottom_line: Lovers of the big Latin-America classic cup with the acidity discreetly tamed by the roast.
title: Colombia Dark Roast Decaf

bottom_line: Anyone who wants to experience how refreshing and exhilarating a really fine extreme light-roasted coffee can be.
title: Decaf

bottom_line: Excellent drip coffee for caffeine-avoiding coffee romantics, and a fragrant, lemony candidate for brewing as iced coffee.
title: Ethiopia Sidamo Decaffeinated

Coffee Origin: Lake Toba region, North Sumatra Province, Sumatra, Indonesia.
bottom_line: Easy-going perfectionists.
title: Sumatra Mandheling Decaf

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a heavy bodied, rich but muted cup.
title: Costa Rica Lomas al Rio Organic

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a classically simple, acidy, slightly fruity American-style breakfast cup.
title: Costa Rica Tarrazu

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a straightforward, mildly acidy cup with a roasty edge. May be forgettable, but it is enjoyable.
title: Costa Rica Tres Volcanos

Coffee Origin: La Luna Estate, Tarrazu growing region, Costa Rica.
bottom_line: "Plunger pot coffee par excellence," according to Kevin.
title: Costa Rica La Luna Tarrazu

Coffee Origin: Tres Rios growing region, Costa Rica.
bottom_line: Those patient enough to wait three or four months, at which time this perhaps too fresh coffee may soften and expand to its full promise. Not sure why I got chocolate and Kevin got chalk, however.
title: Costa Rica La Magnolia

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a balanced roast taste that complements rather than dominates the coffee.
title: Costa Rica Whole Bean, Espresso Roast

bottom_line: Lovers of simple clothing cut from rich materials.
title: Costa Rican Escazu

bottom_line: Hedonists, obviously, and I guess I'm one, given my high rating of this sweet, complex coffee.
title: Costa Rica La Magnolia, 2000/01 crop

Coffee Origin: Tres Rios growing region, Costa Rica.
bottom_line: Classicists who value the simple, intact gesture over the complex and ambiguous.
title: Costa Rica Tres Rios

bottom_line: A classic coffee drinker's classic coffee: displays both the big, resonant dimension of a great Costa Rica with refreshing, fruity complication.
title: Costa Rica Whole Bean, Light Roast

Coffee Origin: Sul de Minas growing region, Minas Gerais State, Brazil
bottom_line: Rich dessert eaters. This subtle, tart-but-sweet, refreshing coffee should nicely balance full-bore pastries and desserts.
title: Fazenda Sao Domingos

bottom_line: This delicately brisk cup with its high-toned complexity should please those who enjoy light but dryly authoritative beverages.
title: Fazenda Vargem Grande

bottom_line: Light-hearted romantics--a profile as subtle and bright as it is exotic.
title: Brazil Fazenda Lagoa Pulped Natural

bottom_line: Those who enjoy tartly sweet, invigoratingly citrus-toned breakfast coffees.
title: Brazil Fazenda Wagner

bottom_line: A round, sweet, rather exotically nuanced cup that should please coffee romantics.
title: Brazil Serra Negra

bottom_line: Those who enjoy high-toned complexity and light-bodied, dry wines.
title: Brazil Fazenda Wagner

bottom_line: An old-time Brazil cup: round, sweet, chocolate-toned. An attractive choice for those who prefer a naturally low-acid cup.
title: Brazil Pedra Azul

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the gentler side of dark roasts: coffees that are roasty without overbearing bitterness.
title: Fazenda Vista Alegre Natural Dry

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a crisply roasty, pear-toned coffee. Milk overwhelms this coffee but a bit of sugar develops the fruit nicely and offsets the hint of bitterness.
title: Brasil Vargem Grande

bottom_line: Should please acidity-avoiders with its subtle, malty sweetness.
title: Brazil Fazenda Lagoa Natural

bottom_line: Substantial body and presence should carry through large volumes of dairy.
title: Brazil

bottom_line: Those who enjoy power in the small cup and complexity in cappuccino.
title: Black Cat Espresso

bottom_line: Probably at its best as a straight shot or cappuccino, but its big body and full-throated complexity make themselves felt even in large quantities of milk.
title: Gusto Crema Blend

bottom_line: I can't imagine a better straight-shot espresso, but in milk invites sweetener.
title: Espresso Blend

bottom_line: The musty fermented fruit tones may put off the purist, but everyone else should enjoy the authoritatively rich, edgy complexity of this blend.
title: Caffé Espresso

bottom_line: More complex at the top than most espresso blends, but a little light at the bottom, which makes it a nice choice for short milk drinks like the cappuccino.
title: Cable Car Blend

bottom_line: Perhaps too intense for straight shots, but relaxes opulently in milk.
title: Espresso Blend

Coffee Origin: Mogiana growing region, Sao Paulo State, Brazil
bottom_line: Less complex than many blended espressos, but satisfying in its powerful balance, particularly in short milk drinks like the cappuccino.
title: Brazil Mogiana Bourbon “Safira”

Coffee Origin: A blend of coffees from southern India.
bottom_line: Caffé latte drinkers and anyone interested in this blend's unusual character and explicit use of robustas and Monsooned Malabars.
title: Malabar Gold Espresso

bottom_line: A quintessential caffé-latte-drinker's espresso, although some also may enjoy the fermented fruit character in the small cup.
title: Oromo Espresso

bottom_line: A cappuccino-drinker's espresso: complex and sweet in short milk.
title: Hawaiian Espresso Molokai Style

bottom_line: Those who enjoy bitter, super-hopped ales or Islay single-malt scotches. Alternatively, those who add sweet syrup to their big-milk espresso drinks.
title: Bizzarri Blend

bottom_line: In milk this is a tall latte drinker's espresso; in the small cup take it with sugar.
title: Espresso Viennese

Roaster Location: Sara Lee Coffee and Tea, New York, New York
bottom_line: Those who want a breakfast cup that is both seductive and classic.
title: Hawaiian Blend

bottom_line: A flat-out, no apologies, old-fashioned American breakfast cup, high-toned and acidy. Forget the latte, buddy, and set this one next to your pancakes (or donuts).
title: Original Blend

bottom_line: Bargain-hunting lovers of Sumatra Mandhelings and other low-toned but roughly rich coffees.
title: Original Bean Coffee

bottom_line: A balanced cup for those for whom refinement is synonymous with understatement. Go easy with the whitener or sweetener or you will overwhelm the coffee.
title: Medium Roast and Grind

bottom_line: A blend with some genuine Kona character, despite the limited amount of actual Kona in the package and the bothersome hint of bitterness.
title: Kona Blend, Special Reserve Light Roast, Whole Bean

bottom_line: The sort of self-effacing, versatile coffee that doesn't call attention to itself, yet three cups later you're still pouring it.
title: 100% Colombian

bottom_line: A take-no-prisoners style of dark roast that lovers of extreme culinary gestures may enjoy.
title: Mayan Black Onyx

bottom_line: Starbucks roasts some very fine single-origin coffees. This Colombia is not one of them. It is one of the few Starbucks coffees I have cupped that fully merits the "Charbucks" slur. Walk on by the supermarket and continue to a Starbucks store (can one be far away?) and opt for the Colombia Narino, a true specialty coffee.
title: Colombia, Whole Bean

Roaster Location: Sara Lee Coffee & Tea, New York, New York
bottom_line: Dark-roast lite. This coffee might make a good budget choice for those who enjoy dark-roast coffees but find the intensity of specialty versions too overbearing.
title: European Roast

bottom_line: This French-roast blend preserves considerably more nuance than many competing small-roaster blends. However, the rubber tones are regrettable. Perhaps they are an anomaly, in which case I can recommend this coffee as a solid and versatile dark-roast choice.
title: French Roast, Whole Bean

Roaster Location: Sara Lee Coffee & Tea, Harrison, New York
bottom_line: People who love the classic red can but aren't too fussy about the classic cup.
title: Coffee

bottom_line: I suspect most dark-roast lovers will be disappointed by this coffee. Rather than the rich, pungent bittersweetness of classic dark roasts we get a cup dominated by faintly nuanced burned cellulose.
title: Cool Java Blend, Special Reserve Dark Roast

bottom_line: Those who prefer a weak, tea-like cup. The extremely light roast has not developed the coffee.
title: Premium Drip Coffee

bottom_line: I guess those who enjoy the odor of freshly cut wood.
title: Costa Rica Roast

Roaster Location: Sara Lee Coffee & Tea, Harrison, New York
bottom_line: Those on extreme budgets who can't stand even a hint of acidity or dark-roast character.
title: Mild Roast

bottom_line: Try it as Cuban-style espresso: pack it into one of the little hour-glass-shaped espresso brewers Italians call caffettiere and after brewing pour the coffee into preheated demitasse cups about half-filled with white sugar, stirring as you pour.
title: Dark Roast

bottom_line: Another study in the impact of cheap Vietnamese mass-processed robusta coffees on the common American cup. (See The Robusta Fuss.)
title: Classic Roast

bottom_line: Those curious about the impact of cheap Vietnamese mass-processed robusta coffees. (See The Robusta Fuss.)
title: Master Blend

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, Big Island of Hawaii, Hawaii
bottom_line: Those who can handle the cabernet-like richness and acidy power of a classic pre-robusta American cup.
title: Brocksen Gate Estate Kona, Pele Roast

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, Big Island of Hawaii, Hawaii
bottom_line: The most purist of professional palates might accuse this coffee of having gained aromatic complexity by absorbing some fermented sugars from the fruit before processing, but, if so, this was a blessed accident. A splendidly seductive coffee, reminiscent of many of the best Ethiopia wet-processed origins.
title: Hawaii Nani Kona Private Reserve, Medium Roast

Coffee Origin: Kona growing region, Big Island of Hawaii, Hawaii
bottom_line: A versatile coffee displaying enough acidity to brighten the cup of traditionalists but just enough bittersweetness and roasty finish to satisfy all but the most extremist of dark-roast lovers.
title: Estate Reserve Kona, Dark Roast

bottom_line: Lovers of authentically tart but sweet lemon or lime pastries; those who crave the exhilarating contradiction of brisk but sweet classic American breakfast coffees.
title: Kona Mountain Coffee, Medium Roast

bottom_line: Lovers of rich, fruity, molasses-laced dessert and breakfast breads
title: Kona Fancy Greenwell Farms

bottom_line: Lovers of the Kona variant of the classic medium-roasted, freshly American breakfast cup.
title: Greenwell Estate Private Reserve 100% Kona

bottom_line: Lovers of subtlety and sweetness.
title: Kona 100% Pure

bottom_line: Those many coffee drinkers who prefer a sweet, low-acid cup overlaid with bitter roasty tones. Very pleasant with milk.
title: Kauai Estate Reserve Peaberry, Dark Roast

bottom_line: Those who enjoy anticipating pleasure more than experiencing it. The aromatics of this coffee are as impressive as any I can remember, but they faded quickly in the cup.
title: Organic Kona, Sakamoto Estate Aged Peaberry, Dark Roast

bottom_line: An interesting variation for those who enjoy the rustic, earthily musty coffees of Sumatra.
title: Muleskinner Dark Roast

bottom_line: Those who like to read the package while they sip. This valve-packed sample, which I pulled from a grocery store aisle in Kona, may have been stale. Those who are fortunate enough to find a fresh bag may find this 100% Kona in its pretty package a plausible last-minute gift to haul home from the Islands.
title: Kona 24-Karat, Light-Medium Roast

bottom_line: Those who are so phobic about brisk, bright coffees that they are willing to sacrifice flavor to flatness.
title: The Other Farm Estate Kona, Vienna Roast

bottom_line: Its dry-yet-sweet, lemon-tart richness should make it a superb late-in-the-day or after-dinner cup.
title: Honduras Strictly High Grown

bottom_line: Lovers of light-bodied, elegant red wines. An impressive expression of the gentle side of Central America coffees.
title: Organic El Salvador

bottom_line: Old-fashioned coffee drinkers who enjoy a brightly acidy but substantial morning cup with summery hints of lemon and flowers.
title: Sierra Madre

bottom_line: A richly low-key coffee that is round and sweet enough to drink black at any time, including after dinner.
title: Organic Mexican

bottom_line: Fast coffee drinkers. An impressively full bodied, rich cup when hot; excellent with whitener.
title: Organic Mexican Altura, Full City Roast

bottom_line: An interesting breakfast cup: rich and smooth but crisp with citrus notes. Drink it hot, before the bitterness sets in.
title: Mexico Chiapas Altura

bottom_line: Those who value dark-roasted coffee more for the bitter tones than the sweet. The relatively full body should carry well in milk, and the bitter tones compensate for enthusiastic additions of sugar.
title: Organic El Salvador

bottom_line: A breakfast coffee candidate bright enough for traditionalists but roasty enough for the dark-roast generation.
title: Dutch Flowers Blend

bottom_line: A quintessential with-milk-and-sugar coffee. The dense, bitter dark-roast character turns sweet and chocolaty in milk.
title: Organic Nicaragua

bottom_line: Full body and authoritative bitterness should help this coffee maintain presence in almost any quantity of milk and sweetener.
title: Organic Aztec Dark

Coffee Origin: San Juan Laguna, Lake Atitlan growing region, Guatemala.
bottom_line: Everyone, though its balance and natural sweetness probably makes it most attractive to those who take their coffee black or with modest amounts of whitener or sugar.
title: Fair Trade Coffee, Light Roast

bottom_line: As simple but appealing as a youthful smile. Excellent black, but big and rich enough to animate milk.
title: Songbird Shade Grown Costa Rican

bottom_line: A well-executed French roast that brings a touch of sweetness and character through the ultimate fires.
title: Sumatra French Roast

Coffee Origin: Gayo Mountain growing region, Aceh Province, northern Sumatra, Indonesia.
bottom_line: Those who love their musty Sumatras and want one that pays the hard-working Sumatran farmers a few pennies more for their efforts.
title: Organic Sumatran Reserve

bottom_line: A pleasant New World variant on the floral-toned, light-bodied, pungent-hearted coffees of Ethiopia.
title: Organic Mexican Select

bottom_line: Definitely not coffee purists. The winey ferment tones make this a coffee for the exuberantly open palate.
title: Guatemala Atitlan “La Voz”

bottom_line: Lovers of the dry and subtle. Perus are harvested in June through August, which means that all of the Perus in this cupping probably are nearly a year old and potentially faded in taste.
title: Organic Peru La Florida

Coffee Origin: San Marcos growing region, southwestern Guatemala.
bottom_line: Slow coffee drinkers. The cup actually improved as it cooled, growing sweeter and better balanced.
title: Organic Guatemala Highlands

bottom_line: Extreme dark-roast aficionados who enjoy some complication in their bittersweet cup.
title: Organic Costa Rican Dark

bottom_line: A fine coffee all around. Particularly impressive with milk or half-and-half, which sweetens the finish and fully develops the chocolate tones.
title: Nicaragua Miraflor

bottom_line: A fine example of the smooth, discreetly dark-roasted style of blend American roasters call Vienna or Viennese. The roastiness is quietly present, but the sugars are caramelized rather than burned, and a touch of brightness livens the cup.
title: Beethoven’s Viennese Blend

Coffee Origin: San Juan Laguna, Lake Atitlan growing region, Guatemala.
bottom_line: An excellent Fair-Trade decaffeinated coffee; just bright enough for classic coffee drinkers but full and rich enough to invigorate milk.
title: Fair Trade Coffee Decaf

bottom_line: Too big, too acidy, and too intense for the Starbucks crowd, but coffee aficionados of the old school should love its grand yet delicately nuanced gesture.
title: Daybreak Morning Blend

bottom_line: A versatile coffee with enough acidity for traditionalists, enough roasty bitterness for coffee-with-milkers, and an ingratiating sweetness that should please all. Blends of two distinctly different roast styles can create a blurred, self-canceling impression, particularly if the dark-roasted part of the blend is too sharp or overbearing, but here the two roast styles work together elegantly.
title: Chuck Roast

bottom_line: Neither Oklahoma City nor the Andes suggest sophisticated decadence, but this is most definitely a decadent 's breakfast blend, sweet and giddy with fermented fruit and lush floral tones. Not a purist 's coffee, but an intriguing one.
title: Pride of the Andes

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a big, roasty-tasting coffee that rumbles rather than whines.
title: Moto Brew

bottom_line: A comfortable walk on the wild side. A little milk will round the bitter finish and develop the sweetness in the cup while preserving the flowers and twisty fruit.
title: Solstice Blend

bottom_line: Chocolate-eating gardeners? It goes against our cultural categories to associate the smell of fresh, moist earth with the taste of chocolate, but they most definitely converge, pleasingly, in exotic blends like this one.
title: Viennese Blend

bottom_line: Those who want some nuts and spice with their roasty-tasting blend.
title: Dolphin Blend

bottom_line: A straightforward coffee, whose simple, strong structure and slightly bitterish finish should stand up well to milk and sweeteners.
title: Polly’s Blend

bottom_line: Those who enjoy a classic but low-key American breakfast coffee with pleasantly understated acidity.
title: Gamble House Blend

bottom_line: Those who prefer morning blends with dark-roast character and exclamation points. An emphatic blend probably best drunk softened with a dollop of milk.
title: Wake Up! Carolina

bottom_line: Those who prefer sweetness and simplicity to range and challenge.
title: Alan’s Blend

bottom_line: Those who love bracingly bright, dry coffees with distinct acidity.
title: Eastern Carolina Morning Blend

Coffee Origin: Maunier Estate, Boquete Valley, Chiriqui Province, Panama.
title: Special Reserve – Green

Coffee Origin: Volcan region west of Volcan Baru, Chiriqui Province, Panama.
title: Specialty Grade – Green

roaster: Cooperativa de Productores de Café Boquete
title: Special Reserve – Green

bottom_line: Anyone interested in experiencing the language-defying forest-toned aromatics of a fine traditionally processed Indonesia coffee.
title: Indonesian Kalossi

bottom_line: Luxurious, fruity and balanced, a candidate for lovers of port wines and brandies.
title: Celebes Kalossi

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the richness, depth, and sweetness of a fine Sulawesi without the edgy bouquet of the forest floor.
title: Sulawesi Toraja

bottom_line: If a coffee as exotic as a Sulawesi can be said to have a classic manifestation, this may be it: clean but big-bodied, rich and resonant.
title: Celebes Toraja Kalossi

bottom_line: The musty tones that join the conventional pleasures of this coffee recommend it to lovers of foods and beverages that tread the rough edge between agreeable and disturbing: edgy spirits like grappa and mescal or the gamier soft-ripened and blue cheeses.
title: Celebes Kalossi

bottom_line: Coffee adventurers. Brings the forest floor to the cup with style and pungent authority.
title: Sulawesi

bottom_line: A shimmer of acidy brightness may make this coffee an attractive exotic alternative for members of the old multiple-black-cup school of American coffee drinking.
title: Celebes

bottom_line: A French-Roast-drinker 's Sulawesi: the bitter bite of an assertive dark roast complicated by a twist of spice.
title: Sulawesi Toraja Dark

bottom_line: Acid-avoiders who enjoy heavy, bittersweet drinks like porter.
title: Aged Sumatra

bottom_line: A versatile coffee for acid-avoiders. Should make a pleasantly bracing drip coffee for breakfast and a dry but chocolaty complement to sweet desserts later in the day.
title: Brazilian Cerrado Capim Branco

bottom_line: Acid-avoiders of the dark-roast school who may enjoy the additional damp-closet complication of the monsooning.
title: India Monsoon Malabar

bottom_line: Those patient enough to wait for another, better version of Blue de Brasil. This is normally a smooth, agreeable coffee. Something went wrong with this particular batch or lot.
title: Blue de Brasil

bottom_line: No one I can think of. Not clear whether the abysmal flavor is the fault of the coffee or the antacid coating. Probably a combination.
title: Tamer Low Acid Coffee Beans, Regular

bottom_line: Acid avoiders in search of a full, sturdy cup without dark-roast distractions.
title: Indian Mysore Plantation

bottom_line: Aside from the disturbing rubbery tones, this coffee is as cozy as a corner in an old Swiss café. Should bring similar comfort to afternoons, desserts, and tricky stomachs. The rubbery sensation may be owing to staleness (too many weeks out of Switzerland
title: Classique High Roasted

bottom_line: Acid-avoiding American breakfast-cuppers.
title: Low Acid Arabica

bottom_line: An acid-avoider 's dark roast with a bit more character and substance than many. In other words, something in addition to burned cellulose made it through the roast.
title: Sumatra

bottom_line: Dropped into a powerfully distinctive coffee, like a Kenya or Guatemala, Coffee Tamer produces a muted but decent low-acid cup.
title: Guatemala Antigua with Coffee Tamer added

bottom_line: Lovers of port, old brandy, and wide-wale corduroy. The fruit is deep, suggestive, and somehow meaty, like the flesh of ripe cherries.
title: Nicaragua Segovia Organic/Fair Trade

bottom_line: American coffee drinkers of the pre-Starbucks school who can handle a big, dry drip coffee. Not for beginners or coffee dilettantes.
title: Organic Mexican Select

bottom_line: Well-dressed activists. Despite the rustic isolation of LaGrande, Oregon, this strikes me as an urbane, little black dress sort of coffee.
title: Elders Blend Gourmet Mayan Coffee

bottom_line: Subtle activists. A gentle but engaging American-style breakfast cup.
title: Aztec Harvest Breakfast Blend

bottom_line: Those who enjoy paradox; in this case, smoky fruit.
title: La Esperanza

bottom_line: Activists who like dry, light red wines. A breakfast coffee with a dash of intrigue.
title: Guatemalan Aroma Roast

bottom_line: Pessimistic activists still hopeful enough to add sugar to their press-pot coffee.
title: Peru Mid-Roast

bottom_line: Stoic activists. A good press-pot coffee. Go ahead and add milk -- this coffee should brush it aside like Sasquatch breaks saplings.
title: Viennese Roast

bottom_line: A breakfast coffee whose acidy brightness is tamed by the roast. A multiple-cup drip coffee for unpretentious activists.
title: Mexican Mid/Light Roast

bottom_line: Crisp rather than brisk, a good multiple-cup breakfast choice for dark-roast aficionados.
title: Fair-Trade Organic Nicaraguan

bottom_line: A fine, versatile American espresso: intriguing in the small cup and substantial in milk. Forgiving in the brewing.
title: Nizza Blend

bottom_line: Enjoy its complex elegance as a straight shot or in moderate amounts of milk. Forgiving in the brewing.
title: Gold Medal Blend

bottom_line: Caffe latte drinkers should not; its virtues vanish in large quantities of milk. Straight shot drinkers looking for refined complexity should.
title: Espresso

bottom_line: Aficionados who pull their espresso carefully will enjoy this blend for its flavor intrigue and dense body. At a slow extraction the mustiness can be bitter and dominating and requires sugar even when married with milk. However, at a relatively quickly paced shot of, say, 17 or 18 seconds after the first drop, the mustiness is tickly, rich, and exhilarating.
title: Espresso Vita

bottom_line: Cappuccino and caffe latte drinkers without pretensions. In the demitasse best with a touch of sugar. A serviceable espresso blend that produces a flavorful shot even when the brewing falls short of perfection.
title: Espresso

bottom_line: A bright, dry espresso that preserves some of the brisk sweetness of good drip coffee.
title: Espresso Ticino

bottom_line: Those who can 't keep the spoon out of the sugar bowl. This is a blend whose robust bitterness calls for marriage with sugar.
title: Espresso Sessuale

bottom_line: Take it in a classic cappuccino (with organic milk, of course). It should make even soy milk taste Italian.
title: Organic Neapolitan Espresso

Coffee Origin: Boquete growing region, Chiriqui Province, Panama.
title: Panamaria Boquete – Green

bottom_line: Only the most determined sensual Scrooge could possibly not like this coffee.
title: Finca La Tacita

bottom_line: A versatile coffee -- just round and roasty enough to complement dessert but assertive and acidy enough for American-style breakfasts.
title: Boquete Region Panamanian Coffee

bottom_line: Lovers of Cuban-seed cigars and big, dry white wines. This coffee is an exception to the typically round, low-key El Salvador cup.
title: El Salvador

bottom_line: Dot-com-ers with a sense of tradition: This is the coffee that those old-fashioned blends in grocery store cans dream about being.
title: Panama La Torcaza

bottom_line: A coffee that demands attention. A two-cup rather than three-cup breakfast coffee -- pair it with something sweet. Should be powerful enough to carry milk and anything else contributed to the cup.
title: Panama – Baru Estate

bottom_line: A coffee for almost any occasion, although its power and completeness may intimidate some palates.
title: Costa Rica Taparto

bottom_line: Too robust and dry for some palates, but should make a sturdy French press coffee that will stand up to some milk and sugar.
title: House Blend

bottom_line: Those who avoid drama, at least in regard to their coffee. Should please coffee drinkers who prefer smoothness to brightness, weight to acidity.
title: Nicaraguan Maragogipe Light Roast

bottom_line: An archetypal American breakfast coffee of the three-cups-with-pancakes variety. Coffee drinkers of the old school should enjoy its dry, light-bodied brightness. Drip-brew it regular strength and take it black.
title: Guatemalan Antigua

bottom_line: Brew it strong, take it with cream, and read the "Coffee Rhapsody" on the side of the bag.
title: El Salvador Borbollon

bottom_line: Should be delicious brewed any time, any way, but I can 't imagine a much better coffee either after dinner or as a straight-shot espresso.
title: Organic Timor

bottom_line: Those with a taste for things gentle, delicate, and sweet without sentiment. Probably best brewed with paper filters to preserve the elegance and refined high notes.
title: Guatemalan Organic

bottom_line: A lovely, versatile coffee with enough acidity to satisfy traditional coffee drinkers but enough low-toned power and complexity to please those who prefer a rounder, fuller cup.
title: Organic East Timor

bottom_line: People fond of big, sweet yet natural culinary gestures. Should make a pleasant stand-alone afterdinner coffee or a voluptuous accompaniment to a chaste dessert.
title: Papua New Guinea Organic

Coffee Origin: Lake Atitlan basin, south central Guatemala.
bottom_line: This is not a purist 's coffee, but the rich, sweet ferment tones should delight those genial palates that enjoy richly ambiguous desserts. Should do splendidly in a French press.
title: Guatemala Atitlan

bottom_line: Try it filter-drip brewed with sugar or black with compensatingly rich, sweet desserts or pastries.
title: El Paraiso

bottom_line: Minimalist coffee drinkers? Should provide satisfaction without distraction.
title: Peruvian Organic

bottom_line: Perhaps those who can 't make up their minds whether they prefer a traditionally bright American cup or a bitterish dark-roast one.
title: Organic Bolivian

bottom_line: The darkish roast and floral notes should make this a decent after-dinner decaffeinated coffee for the environmentally fastidious. The dry, brittle beans may produce too much silt for French-press brewing. Try this one brewed extra strong through a paper filter.
title: Decaf Organic Sumatra Gayo Mountain

bottom_line: Morose flower lovers? Just kidding. The floral tones may make this blend a pleasant change of pace for lovers of extreme darks roasts.
title: Organic French Roast

bottom_line: A clean, levitating Sumatra without the usual musty, earthy, gritty baggage. More Mozart than Beethoven, this is an optimistic Sumatra for sunny mornings and drip brewing.
title: Sumatra Decaf

bottom_line: An almost overpowering coffee in the classic American mode. Put on a plaid flannel shirt and drink it out of the heaviest mug on the shelf. Dark-roast drinkers and latte bibbers steer clear. The idea of a coffee this robust without caffeine seems a little odd, like a cross between a Harley and a Vespa.
title: House Blend Decaf

bottom_line: Those who want something a bit different, in this case something mouthfilling, sweet-toned and spicy. Not for lovers of the typically acidy, wine-and-berry-toned Kenya. Makes an unusual and interesting espresso.
title: Kenya AA Swiss Water Decaf

bottom_line: A fine drip coffee for those who prefer a light, aromatic cup with just enough acidity to keep things lively but not too tart. After dinner try it drip, double strength in a demitasse.
title: Appassionato Decaf

bottom_line: An ingratiating, comfortable coffee best drunk black or lightly whitened. A tea-drinker 's coffee, but brewed strong it should be a pleasant finisher to dinner.
title: Sumatra Decaf

bottom_line: Lovers of the rough dark roasts of the West Coast and Southwest who want a little value added in the form of winy fruit tones. Brew it French Press and enjoy the bracing contrast of fruity sweetness and pungent grit.
title: Decaf Pure Mocha Java

bottom_line: Diner revivalists, those who look back to American breakfast coffees before they were ruined by robustas. Improves as it cools, making it even more appropriate for the multiple cups of American tradition.
title: Mountain Country Decaf House Blend

bottom_line: Those who love musty Sumatras, the kind that taste like the back corner of damp closets. (You know who you are.) The sweetness of this coffee turns the mustiness almost elegant.
title: Sumatra Swiss Water Decaf

bottom_line: Adventurers willing to risk a little disappointment on the way to pleasure. The fact that Colombia coffees like this one are produced on small farms and prepared and dried by the farmers, then combined into larger lots, probably accounts for the unevenness of this sporadically splendid coffee.
title: Decaf Colombian Excelso

bottom_line: An unusual Guatemala taste, but not entirely uncharacteristic. "Smokiness" and "chocolate" used to be two of the epithets applied to Guatemala coffees, although I haven 't heard them used much recently. Should make a very nice drip-brewed coffee for those who like a brisk but not acidy cup. Try it unsweetened with a sweet pastry.
title: Decaffeinated Guatemalan SWP

bottom_line: A wonderful blend name, appropriate to Eureka, a logging and fishing town whose austere setting and no-bull North Coast attitude may make a rough, dark-roast blend without much nuance like this one perfectly appropriate.
title: Decaf Good, Strong Blend

bottom_line: Dark-roast lovers too lazy to grind their own coffee and too busy to shop for a better dark roast at a similar price at a specialty coffee store.
title: House Blend

bottom_line: Not for those who love very dark roasts for their intensity, but rather for those who choose them to avoid acidity and brightness.
title: Maxwell House Rich French Roast

bottom_line: Supermarket shoppers too hurried and vague to know the difference between a name and a coffee.
title: House Blend

bottom_line: People whose senses are on the same severe budget as their bank account.
title: Folgers Coffee House French Roast

bottom_line: People with neither noses nor money.
title: Hills Brothers French Roast

bottom_line: Trader Joe 's targets the budget gourmet, and this coffee, inexpensive yet glisteningly aromatic and full of idiosyncrasy and character, certainly supports Joe 's business plan. However, neither Javas nor Ethiopia Mokas are consistent coffees, so you may have to buy now to taste what I tasted.
title: Moka Java

bottom_line: Brewed drip this is coffee equivalent of comfort food: ingratiating, undemanding, agreeable. Lacks intensity and range, but sound, round and satisfying.
title: MJB Hawaiian Blend

bottom_line: A good, low-key cup in the bittersweet, darker roast mode. Not particularly cheap, however, and as a specialty (rather than supermarket) dark-roast coffee I would place it in the middle of the pack.
title: Breakfast Blend

bottom_line: If traditions can come in a can, canned Colombias like this one are an American tradition. My parents brewed canned Colombia in their Danish modern Chemex in 1960. Compared to the listless, plodding nonentities of canned blends it competes against, this coffee is a virtual thoroughbred.
title: Yuban 100% Colombian

bottom_line: People without olfactory functions.
title: Folgers Aroma Roasted

bottom_line: People who enjoy licking sugar off tires. (Sorry.)
title: Chock Full O’Nuts

bottom_line: Those who love musty Sumatras to the point of masochism or shoppers who are desperate for a really cheap whole bean coffee. I generally don 't care for musty coffees, but in deference to those who do, I have trained myself to accept and even enjoy mustiness in moderation. But the musty sensation in this coffee quite exceeds moderation.
title: Original Blend

bottom_line: Since people who like dark roasts tend to value intensity over depth and subtlety, this coffee should suit them fine, particularly if they 're on a budget. Brew it strong to offset the relatively light body.
title: French Roast

bottom_line: An adequate dark-roast coffee for dark-roast drinkers on a severe budget.
title: Dark Roast

Coffee Origin: Pluma Hidalgo village, Oaxaca State, Mexico.
bottom_line: A fine breakfast coffee, carrying with it hopes for a new millennium in which the peasant coffee farmers of the world begin to share some of the wealth that we lavish on much lesser pleasures in life than a coffee like this one, a coffee as everyday yet as amazing as a loving morning kiss.
title: Aztec Harvest Breakfast Blend

bottom_line: Clear yet complex, bright yet rich, fruity yet austere. A breakfast coffee from the old millennium to start the new.
title: Kenya AA Grand Cru

bottom_line: Refined yet sturdy, surprising yet inevitable, a treasure from the old millennium and an afterdinner coffee to usher in the new.
title: Kenya AA

bottom_line: Those who find Kenya too acidy, Yirgacheffe too flowery, Sumatra too funky. Those who admire classic simplicity, whether it be Mozart or Joe Montana.
title: La Minita Estate Tarrazu

bottom_line: Those who find medium-roast coffees too acidy and dark-roast coffees too pungent. Serve it strong and revel in its enveloping sweetness, or brew it as espresso and try it straight up, without sugar.
title: Santos Best

bottom_line: Cigar smokers, single-malt fanciers, bleu cheese lovers, anyone who values the odd tastes that bring the dark corners of nature to our palates.
title: Sumatra Mandheling

bottom_line: Think the musty dampness of basements and old boards. A childhood memory perhaps. Then imagine just a hint of that taste in your cup. If this sounds like a strange introduction to what some consider a gourmet treat, remember, you may have thought soft-ripened cheese smelled like your father 's socks the first time you tasted it too.
title: Sumatra Mandheling

bottom_line: Any way you drink this coffee you should be able to taste the primeval, complex sweetness of fruit drying in the mountain sun.
title: Yemen Mattari

bottom_line: Perhaps what we all yearn for in our busy holiday compensations for the dull days of winter is the combination of grandeur and intimacy that this coffee suggests, as simultaneously gigantic in size and elegant in silhouette as the volcanoes that float like visions over the streets and farms of Antigua.
title: Finca La Tacita, Estate Peaberry

bottom_line: Think wildness domesticated, a provisionally tamed cheetah under the Christmas tree. Wine, fruit, chocolate, but a little bit of growl too. Try it in a French Press with something spicy and simple; pumpkin pie, say.
title: Celebration Caffe

bottom_line: Three cups, brewed medium strength drip, should bring spring even into dark February kitchens before a plunge into the slush.
title: Vermont Country Blend

bottom_line: Presumably, elves with a taste for dry, pungent, tartly fruity coffee. But if all the elves are north for the holidays buy it for black-coffee drinkers who think sweet is sissy. Or supply the sweetness yourself: This is a coffee that should stand up to major amounts of milk and sugar.
title: The Elves Imperial Breakfast Blend

bottom_line: People who love Hawaii but hate Waikiki. The curious low-toned funkiness of this coffee brings a little ramshackle country charm to the winter table along with the palm-tree memories.
title: Malulani Estate

bottom_line: It 's not too fanciful to suggest that this rich, low-toned Caribbean cup brings a bit of the luminous mists of the Blue Mountains to our often less-than-luminous winter days. And since this is winter, I 'm sure no one will let this coffee cool down enough to let that hint of hardness disturb the deep, smooth completeness of the cup.
title: Jamaican Blue Mountain – Mavis Bank

bottom_line: The combination of dry, brisk mid-tones and earthy bottom produces a quirky breakfast coffee with additional murkily exotic after dinner possibilities. Try it brewed drip with a shot of brandy and a dollop of whipped cream.
title: Christmas Blend

bottom_line: Holiday entertainers too sophisticated for brassy artificially flavored coffees but who want a change of pace. Probably best drunk black or with spirits (brandy, rum, grappa) and a little brown sugar. May not be sturdy enough to support much milk or cream.
title: Holiday Blend with Spices

bottom_line: Bittersweet chocolate lovers, wide-wale corduroy wearers, haters of breakfast blends, evening fire contemplators.
title: Italian Roast

bottom_line: Those who like things that are both rugged and elegant. Intense without sentiment, pungent without burned tones, this coffee is energetic enough to please on holiday mornings but roasty enough to taste right in the evening with pie slathered with ice cream.
title: Christmas Blend

bottom_line: A cocooning-around-the-fire coffee, big but undemanding, a solid platform for dessert. Brew it strong in a French press and add a little half and half.
title: Turkish Delight

bottom_line: Most extremely dark-roasted coffees strike me as more skeletal than macho owing to their thin body. This dark roast has enough substance to justify the hair on its namesake 's chest.
title: Mountain Man Blend

bottom_line: Lovers of charred but interesting coffees.
title: Roaster Blend

bottom_line: Lovers of the wild, deep, archetypal dry-processed coffees of Yemen and the Horn of Africa.
title: Ethiopian Harrar “Horse”

bottom_line: Those who like dark-roast coffees have never struck me as admirers of the ethereal or delicate, but if some of you are out there, try this one.
title: Ethiopia Washed Sidamo, Vienna Roast

bottom_line: Lovers of light-bodied, fruit-toned dark roasts. I 'd brew it drip and spare the sugar.
title: Organic Timor Aifu, Vienna Roast

bottom_line: Lovers of complex, duskily ambiguous darker-roasted Indonesia coffees.
title: Paia Blend

bottom_line: An adventurer 's coffee, hearty but exotic.
title: Ethiopia Harrar

bottom_line: This splendid, versatile coffee should do as well for French press romance as it does for three cups on a bright, workaday morning. Or try it on the porch Saturday afternoon, iced with a little half-and-half.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe

bottom_line: People who watch the X-Games on television; skydivers; people with studs in their tongues; admirers of Baudelaire.
title: Mocca Java Blend

bottom_line: A touch too dry for my taste (the aftertaste borders on astringent) but old-time, three-cups-with-breakfast, knit-the-holes-in-your-socks-together American coffee drinkers should love it.
title: Mexican Maya

bottom_line: Hearty breakfasters.
title: Oakhurst Morning

bottom_line: People who prefer simpler bouquets of the same flower rather than complex bouquets of many.
title: Ethiopian Yirgacheffe

Coffee Origin: Cauca Department, southwestern Colombia. Traditional market name: Popayan.
title: Popayan – Green

roaster: Café Organico Mesa de Los Santos
title: Bucaramanga – Green

bottom_line: Those who enjoy the charred sweetness of coffee that absorbed too much heat at the end of the roast.
title: Guatemalan Antigua, 1999

bottom_line: Chocolate lovers with sophisticated palates.
title: Guatemala Huehuetenango ’99

bottom_line: A hearty cup for urban campfires.
title: Antigua Bella Carmona ’99

bottom_line: The Montana Coffee Traders logo includes charmingly retro silhouettes of two figures in cowboy hats enjoying coffee in front of a fire. This Guatemala, with its hefty body and old-fashioned, take-no-prisoners acidity, should do well around campfires and cowboy hats, not to mention Moscow winters.
title: Guatemalan El Injerto, 1999

bottom_line: Elegant rather than forceful, this is a superb but somewhat atypical Antigua. Should do splendidly in a drip preparation for mornings and afternoons.
title: Guatemalan Antigua, 1999

bottom_line: An archetypal American breakfast coffee: solid, satisfying, unassuming.
title: Guatemala Fraijanes, 1999

bottom_line: A classicist's drip coffee: bold, simple, arresting.
title: Guatemala Antigua, 1998

bottom_line: Thrill-seeking sophisticates.
title: Guatemala Antigua Organic, 1999

bottom_line: Those who take their coffee strong and sweeten the cup.
title: Guatemala, 1999

bottom_line: Those who find medium-roasted Latin-American coffees too bright and dark-roast coffees too sharp. A simple, round, mouth-filling cup.
title: Guatemala Atitlan, 1998

bottom_line: Dark-roast aficionados with subtle palates. The roast character here is gently complex and completely free of charred sharpness. Should make a superb French-press coffee and a rather light-bodied but fragrant straight espresso.
title: Guatemala, 1998 / 1999

bottom_line: Environmentalists who like quiet parties where nobody shouts and everyone makes sense.
title: Nicaragua Organic

bottom_line: Name-droppers who like a famous coffee that won't embarrass them when they open the can.
title: Jamaican Blue Mtn Dark Roast

bottom_line: Merlot lovers.
title: Kenya

bottom_line: Suave bohemians.
title: Bohemian Blend

bottom_line: Admirers of sweetness without sentiment.
title: Best of Africa Blend

bottom_line: Anyone in search of an original and seductive variation on the dark-roast bittersweet theme.
title: Turkish Blend

bottom_line: Cabernet lovers.
title: Kenya

bottom_line: Lovers of nuance-obliterating cultural gestures: very hot food, super-garlicked sauces.
title: French Roast

bottom_line: Bittersweet syndrome fans lost in the suburbs or strange cities.
title: Italian Roast

bottom_line: Film-noir and fog fans. I imagine Bogart drinking it at an Ocean Beach diner when the blonde first slinks in: fundamentally bitter with a deceptive sweetness at the beginning.
title: Fogbuster Blend

bottom_line: Hot food lovers who like a little complexity to survive on the far side of the jalapenos.
title: French Roast

bottom_line: Name-droppers who want a coffee that comes very close to living up to its famous name.
title: Jamaica Blue Mtn:Old Tavern #1

bottom_line: Those who want coffee without caffeine and coffee substance without frivolity.
title: Kenya Decaf

bottom_line: Coffee adventurers who want an exotic but safe trip. This is a simpler, lighter, brighter, less funky version of the traditional and twistily complex Yemen Mocha cup.
title: Moka

bottom_line: Those (to use a gendered analogy) who prefer Brooks Brothers to Italian designers.
title: Hawaiian Kona Extra Fancy

bottom_line: Lovers of a full, low-toned cup with an edge of pungency.
title: Fifth Anniversary Blend

bottom_line: Those who admire both elegance and exuberance.
title: Ethiopia Yirgacheffe

bottom_line: Anyone who thinks all coffees taste the same. Coffee purists may be offended by the occasional lush twist in the Yemen aftertaste, but the public seems more than willing to overlook it given the depth, power, and dry fruit intrigue of the best Yemen. Recently I gave a coffee talk to the general public preceded by an informal tasting. The audience overwhelmingly preferred a Yemen to three other very distinguished origins.
title: Yemen Mocha

Coffee Origin: Honomalino Estate, Kona, Big Island, Hawaii
bottom_line: A classic American breakfast coffee: the apotheosis of brisk and bottomless.
title: Kona – Honomalino Extra Fancy

Coffee Origin: Honomalino Estate, Kona, Big Island, Hawaii
bottom_line: One of those delicately complex, breezy Konas that seems ready to lift right out of the cup and generate hibiscus blossoms on the ficus. Nostalgics should have no problem associating this coffee with languorous Hawaii afternoons.
title: Kona – Honomalino Peaberry

bottom_line: A good coffee to drink black with cherry pie.
title: Colombian Supremo Popayan

bottom_line: I've always considered Sumatra a romantic's coffee owing to its complexity and richness. If so, this richly light Sumatra is for low-key romantics who prefer Isabel Allende to Marquez.
title: Sumatra Decaf

bottom_line: Those willing to slow down (the absence of caffeine should help) and let the sweetness come to them.
title: Organic CO2 Decaf Peru

bottom_line: Lovers of excess without sentiment.
title: Mocha Java Style Blend

bottom_line: Lovers and optimists.
title: Tchoupitoulas Blend

bottom_line: Dark-roast lovers in pursuit of sweetness and sublety.
title: Koloa Estate Dark Roast

bottom_line: I'm giving a split grade for this one to honor my split coffee personality: 85 on behalf of the romantic that admires the sweet, complex intrigue of the cup and 75 on behalf of the purist who recognizes that in any other context except aging the hard taste that survives in the center of this particular aged profile would be considered a defect.
title: Aged Sumatra

bottom_line: A sexy variation on the classic washed profiles of Latin America. Try it medium-strength, filter-drip, black or almost.
title: Java Estate

bottom_line: The highest-rated traditionally-processed Indonesia in the cupping. Pungent/sweet Indonesia character combined with a moderately dark roast would seem to make this coffee a particularly agreeable choice for afterdinner press-pot brewing.
title: Sumatra Mandheling

bottom_line: Low-key but cleanly complex, this might make a good multi-cup, filter-drip breakfast coffee for those who find Latin-American breakfast coffees too acidy or brisk.
title: Papua New Guinea Sigri

bottom_line: Those willing to put up with a little hardness for a cupful of intrigue.
title: Sumatra Gayo Mountain

bottom_line: A solid, no-frills organic Indonesia for solid, no-frills organic coffee drinkers.
title: Organic Timor

bottom_line: Another hardish-Sumatra-lover's hardish Sumatra. Brew it strong and drink it with milk and sugar.
title: Sumatra Mandheling

bottom_line: A good choice for those whose taste in Indonesias leans toward the hard rather than soft. Mine doesn't, hence the lukewarm rating.
title: Sulawesi Kalossi DP

bottom_line: The rich, spicy hardness might round out nicely under the ministrations of milk and sugar.
title: Organic Timor

bottom_line: Either romantics who sufficiently enjoy the exotic appeal of aging coffee to overlook this particular aged reality, or those who genuinely enjoy hard-tasting coffees.
title: Aged Sumatra Mandh. Pawani

bottom_line: To my palate this coffee approaches the classic Java cup. Try it while you have the chance.
title: Java

bottom_line: Organic and earthy: These are good words for a lot of folks in my patch of the urban jungle.
title: Organic Sumatra
